Holy cow. I hope more people read this book before seeing the movie. (I have been patiently waiting to finish to finally rend the film.)This book is CRAZY and GOOD. I spent the first half of the book convinced that it was all very ho-hum and by the numbers, I knew twists and turns were coming but it felt like the set up was really drawn out. But when the Author flips the switch...the path you walk down is well worth the set up. The book plays with themes that I think men and women can identify with. Depending on your background I can see different people reacting differently. I understand if some women feel it paints women in a bad light. But I think it paints men and women in a bad light. Both male and female leads have flaws (some bigger then others, but it's a crime drama for crying out loud. Someone has to be guilty.) Without spoiling anything for any reader out there, the book is well written and thrill ride. I stayed up nights finishing the final chapters. It's unsettling, yet fun, you find yourself rooting for one side then the other. The actual final pages don't sit as well as the rest of the book, but in a story with crazy, out of control characters, their final place in this world is perhaps the craziest of all.
Clearly Gone Girl is clever and devious.  It has you thinking you know what is going on, then changes everything.  It even makes you speculate what will happen in the future for the characters!
It's a phenomenon that an author can write a commercial thriller with literature level prose.  Flynn has created this novel with the powerful magnet that places the reader in the mindset of the characters and we face our darker side.  For those that loved Gone Girl this acceptance is closer to awareness than the reviewers who hated it. Those are the individuals in denial.  Flynn is illustrating the twisted combustion of Amy and Nick whose darker side is closer to the surface, and she illustrates that Rand, Marybeth and Go have buried their evil by supporting them. I could elaborate on the plot, subplot, story line and theme, but 4,000 plus reviews detail this quite well. My only annoyance with Gone Girl is several times Flynn addresses the reader on proper grammar.  (Nick and me) then she writes yes, that's proper to show us she intentionally wrote it that way, while assuring those that have always held to the belief that it should be Nick and I. She does this so we know she's aware that she's not committing a grammatical error: a trivial point, but a little distracting. .Gone Girl has become a part of my psyche and I will volley the consequence for quite some time questioning if that's a good thing. That's how it's done, darlin'.
This novel had received a lot positive and interesting reviews from other readers, so I had to see for myself.  Sometimes, I can read the reviews and totally disagree with them once I have read the book.  In this case, I have to say that the book lived up to the reviews and kept me interested throughout.  I actually read the book in less than twenty-four hours because I simply could not put it down.That being said, I was left wanting more in the end.  I will not go into specifics so as not spoil the ending for other readers.  However, I wanted a finite resolution at the end of the book.  I completely understand why the author ended it at that point in the story, to leave readers wondering, wanting retribution, but I wanted to see the aftermath play out a little bit more.  I'm not one to check the page numbers on my Kindle, so when I read the last sentence, and flipped the page, I felt a bit like ""What? That's it?"".Overall, I loved the book and the author did a fantastic job of plotting the novel and developing the characters.  I would most definitely recommend this book to anyone who loves great mystery and suspense novels.  To the author:  there must be a sequel!
