Keeps you reading to find out what happens next, with a psychological tone throughout it that I love. Flynn has a way of showing the characters experiences, damages, and intent behind their actions. She leaves you relating with the worst of people in an uncomfortable, wonderful way. A lot of the negative reviews are about the nasty/dark characters, so I guess I would say don't read this if you are looking for a book where you can pretend to relate to the perfect perky main character? Flynn's books have characters who's darkness has taken over them; people uncomfortable with their own bit of darkness generally don't like to read a book where it's teased out. Another point on the negative reviews was the ending. Little bit of a spoiler: dont read this book if to enjoy it you'll need the 'bad guy' to get his comeuppance. Not happening. This book is edgy and genius and I encourage you to read it.
I love this story, it's construction, and it's execution. The entire time you're reading it you know the two paths that are possible, but the author keeps you interested in finding out which path is the actual path and how the story unfolds along that path. She also avoids giving the reader closure, which is much more intriguing than a clear-cut ending. I know that many readers are upset by not getting their closure, but this isn't Disney. I also love the author's dark side - she sounds as though she had a good family and a very 'undark' upbringing, but she is keenly attuned to the darkness in people, which I do not expect from someone who had a good family. Maybe I'm naive, or maybe this author is a keen study of people, and/or maybe she gets her homework done. All I can say is kudos to her. Add me to the list of her many admirers. I look forward to reading more from Ms. Flynn.
I could not put this book down for a second. It's, well, to borrow Flynn's prose, WICKED GOOD AND AMAZING. Her writing style is streamlined for maximum pleasure and speed. Her voice is edgy, modern - totally NOW. She doesn't completely buy into every grammar rule and her almost-neologisms are spot on wit and fun. This book made me actually experience the emotions of the characters. At various times I was laughing out loud, totally turned-on, or mercilessly edgy and nervous. The character development is as precise as if Flynn were a PhD in abnormal psychology and she captures the interplay between two damaged people in a relationship no better than if she'd lived it herself. The plot is so damn evil it's positively delicious even if a bit far-fetched. Truly an intense read from first word to last. Will escape you from your own troubles for sure - if only, like me, for one night.
I had read Gillian Flynn's previous novel ""Dark Places"" and enjoyed it quite a bit. But in her latest book ""Gone Girl"", she definitely takes her craft up a notch. It is simply one of the best books I've read in a while, certainly the best this year.It remains amazing how Flynn came make you care or at least be interested in what happens to her regularly unlikeable characters.  In short, make the unlikeable, likeable.  The novel contains the requisite great mystery and twists that make it a jaw dropping page-turner but what continues to set Flynn apart from other mystery-crime authors of the day is her wonderful prose and character introspection.  She delves into not only the how but also the why.  The book is as much a mystery as a study on relationships and society mores.  I would definitely recommend this book to everyone even if its not your usual genre.
