Best.psychological.thriller.ever!I'm normally very articulate, detailed and pragmatic in my book reviews, or I try to be.  However, there is no summary of plots, sub categories or analyzing of characters that will prepare you for the sociopath that these pages hide away for so long.What I can offer is this; just when you're sure you know what's going on, what is coming next, you're wrong. BOOM- another bombshell, CRACK- another twist, WHAM- another surprise. By the end you will feel drained, gutted and exhausted trying to keep up.But what makes this a five star read? I laughed, I literally laughed out loud often and earnestly A LOT throughout the first half of this book then sat slack jawed the entire second half, violently scrolling my finger along my tablet to turn the digital page.Just amazing.
Gone Girl is the most fun I have had with a new book in many years.  Have to think when I have enjoyed and looked forward to the ""next chapter""  or should I say the next click?  I am reading on a Kindle right now.  A terrible confession since I am a retired English teacher of the old-fashioned kind.  Would it spoil anything to say it's such delightful stream-of-conscious, play-by-play, action?  The best clear-cut, no unnecessary verbosity, capturing the personality and mind set of each character, well distinguished one from the other. Lots of surprises, (not distracting) but ones you can't wait for the character to find out (because you already know!). Oh, the fun of it.  But this is not for the feint at heart.  No, not for a second.  Well thought out plot to the very end.That's all I'll tell you.  You have to read it for yourself.
Holy cow!Writing a review for this book without giving anything away will be tricky so this may be a shorter review.Nick and Amy are just hours away from celebrating their 5th wedding anniversary when Nick, still at work, gets a call from his neighbor that his cat is outside.  When Nick arrives home, he finds that not only is his cat outside but that his front door is wide open and his wife is missing.The police arrive, a report is filed, the crime scene examined and Nick is continually repeating his innocence.  However, no matter what Nick says he still becomes the prime suspect because Amy is so very clever and not just clever but patient.The story is unimaginable and I'm now afraid of the author Gillian Flynn because for her to make up with this story is scary.Definite recommend!
A must read! Couldn't put down my kindle. Read it before the movie comes out. Ben affeck will be playing the role of the husband.
The book is full of so many twists and turns that will keep you guessing till the very end. I don't want to give spoilers but will say that the book begins with a story that could have been ripped from the headlines - a beautiful young wife has gone missing; the husband and family make a heartfelt plea for her safe return to the media; pundits start speculating that the husband is the culprit... What the book is actually about will blow your mind as that familiar story is rewritten in an intriguing and shocking way! You will see characters who are flawed, some who are relatively good, and some who are chillingly evil. Just when you think things can't get worse or nothing will surprise you farther, something will happen and you will be taken aback again at another plot twist. If you like good mystery/thrillers, then this is the book for you!
Gone Girl was an  excellent read. The first few diary entries I found a bit tedious and confusing, however, this is only a minor complaint. Written in the style of one chapter about Nick and the next about Amy, it made for very interesting reading, keeps you wanting to know what happens next to both characters.Throughtout the book your feelings for both characters change from dislike to like, back again to dislike, then feeling sorry for him or her, in the end you dont know who to dislike more, Nick or Amy!!!!  Very clever writing.An excellent read, keeps you wanting to read on, no matter what's happening around you, just to find out what happens in the next chapter and how the story ends.....but that's the worst thing about a good book.....the end.....then you have to find another good book to follow!!!
Ms. Flynn is a genius - she has a keen eye and ear and writes beautifully.  She captures the voices of her two characters perfectly, and while I usually do not care for books with alternating chapters for various characters to air perspectives, Ms. Flynn makes it work and if anything, her technique enhances the novel.She has extraordinary eye and ear for contemporary culture and captures the essence of male vs. female; Manhattan vs. Missouri; marriage vs. courtship; upper class vs. lower class; et al.She is neutrally critical as well - no NYC snobbery here - almost scientific in her perspective, she pins everyone down for close inspection by a critical eye - a social lepidopterist of the first order.And she manages to be wonderfully funny, witty, humorous.One of the best books I've read in a long time.
This book was pretty fantastic! I've read Gillian Flynn's other two novels, and I've enjoyed them. Although I don't know if ""enjoyed"" is really the right word. They are very dark, twisted and creepy. ""Gone Girl"" is no exception, but I did find it less dark than her first two, which isn't a bad thing. This book appeals more to the mainstream, but it's still pretty dark, and well-written, and okay I will use the word enjoyable. I kept turning to my partner to say, I have to tell you what just happened...The story is told from two different points of view. Flynn does a wonderful job of giving unique voices to these characters. There is a big twist near the middle of the novel. It wasn't totally surprising, but it does change the pace of the story, and things pick up after that.I'm not sure how I feel about the ending. I still have to give it some thought to see how I feel about. Totally worth checking out, if you like mystery, suspense, and dark, twisted novels.
I read this book during the summer, and then my book club selected it as our September book, so I read it again!  I really intended to only hit the highlights on this second read, but I was immediately pulled back into the story and probably enjoyed it even more as I watched the twists and turns develop.  It's a ""he said, she said"" concept, with more than the usual surprises.  Both main characters have major flaws and it is hard to work up much sympathy for either one...until...A chilling ending; I can recite the last few sentences by memory and shiver every time.  If you have read ""Defending Jacob"", it is equivalent to the sentence in that book--""And then the girl disappeared.""A rollicking two-time read for me--highly recommend to fans of both mystery and personal relationship genres.
It kept my interest piqued throughout the whole book. A very  unique  presentation. I am anxious to see the movie version.
Never saw that coming. The beginning was SLOW. I stuck it out and then I couldn't put it down. I can't wait for the movie.
Chilling prose is a very apt description. The writing is terrific, the story dark and enthralling. One of the best books I've read because it has both great prose and a great plot. If, however, you're looking for a happy ending, look elsewhere. Clearly, some who have left reviews were angry they didn't get that. This is a twisted psychological tale and not intended for the faint of heart. I wouldn't advise reading plot summaries, since spoilers will truly ruin the book for you. A woman has disappeared from a troubled marriage. The story is told from her point of view and from the husband's point of view. That's all the plot I'd want to know going in. Flynn does a fantastic job of slowly revealing these complex characters and events until she leaves you breathless. Good luck putting this one down.
This book tortured me...because there really is no good ""stopping point"", which meant that the times that I read it at work and my breaks ended I was left hanging on the edge of some new, always startling discovery or plot twist. I ended up staying up all night finishing the last 45% of the book. The effect/enjoyment of reading Gone Girl is absolutely impossible to explain. While it was one of the most twisted and disturbing stories that I have ever read, it also felt very real, very believable, very ""oh my god, this is such a dose of relationship reality and that is scary!"" Gillian Flynn's portrayal of the Dunne's marriage and the decline thereof is strikingly realistic while also being out of this world nuts. I did guess partway through what had actually happened to Amy, but it had no effect whatsoever on the enjoyment I got out of the rest of the story, and there were so many elements that I could never in a million years have guessed that completely made up for that tiny bit of letdown. This book is utterly absorbing, thrilling and absolutely BRILLIANT! What I wouldn't give to see into Gillian Flynn's mind..and then get back out quickly!
I could barely keep myself away from this book.  I was up at all hours of the night reading this, dying to know what happens next.  I had no idea it was a ""crime novel,"" so to speak.  But it is so much more than that.  In fact, had I thought it was a crime novel at the outset, I might have never picked it up).  To begin with, it's exceptionally well-written, with well-defined characters, and thought provoking insight into the Venus/Mars relationship between the genders.  This author understands people and relationships and human nature.  The ending was not what I necessarily wanted, but it is in keeping with the characters.  I absolutely loved it and immediately recommended it to friends.  I hear they are making a movie and intend to change the ending.  Interesting.  READ IT!!
