“There’s something disturbing about recalling a warm memory and feeling utterly cold.”Gillian Flynn’s Gone Girl was chilling and disturbing, with dark notes on relationships, marriage and love. It begins on the day of Amy Elliott and Nick Dunne’s fifth anniversary where Amy has disappeared. As the police investigates all clues seem to lead to Nick, but he swears that he has nothing to do with it. Going back and forth with Nick’s narrative and Amy’s ‘past’, the novel in the first part is structured as a ‘whodunit’. But nothing is what it appears to be and I was completely drawn into it wanting to unravel the Amy’s mystery and Nick’s thoughts. ‘Gone Girl’ left me feeling a little bit cold and scared!
This was definitely a page turner and when I first started reading the book, it had some similarities to a true story case from a few years ago, but then it had it's twists and turns and became a very good psychological thriller.  The ending was certainly unexpected.  Wanted to see a satisfying resolution, but the author did a good job with all of the characters and I had a hard time putting the book down.  Found myself looking for spare time so I could get back to my reading.  I am now looking forward to seeing the movie, although the movie usually isn't as good as the book, but this might surprise me.  It will be a fast read because it grabs you from the start and you can't wait to see what happens next.
This book delivers all the suspense and surprises hoped for in a thriller. Told alternately from the perspectives of the two main characters, a married couple named Nick and Amy. Little in this book is as it first appears, but the author does a great job of making each twist seem believable and realistic. This story is an in-your-face reminder that no matter how well you know someone, you never know them completely. It's easy to see why this story has become so immensely popular. I imagine there are a whole lot more people out there these days, sneaking a glance at their partner across the room and wondering what secrets they may not know.Michael Travis Jasper, Author of the Novel ""To Be Chosen
Great summer read, or winter, fall or spring for that matter.  Amy and NIck embody the image of the self absorbed metro couples today.  Amy's perfectionism, Nick's disconnect represents our computer obsessed culture.  How well do we really know the people we are with, when we spend our day in virtual relationships.  Do we even know how to discover each other anymore? Suspenseful, yes.  Did I guess ( I don't want to give anything away), yes, did it matter- no!  Like the rest of the book, the ending was a necessary commentary on the morally bankrupt society we find ourselves in today.  Filled with cliches, I loved the twist at the end.  Did it make me uncomfortable- for sure- and that's a good book!
I'm about 75% of the way through this book, and am loving it so far. The author's writing style is very accessible but elegant to such an extent that I'll purchase her other books regardless of what they're about. As for this story, it's been totally captivating from the start and really draws you in by the way it's told from the first person perspective of two different people throughout. Not only is the main story riveting (did this guy kill his wife) but it also generates a real emotive response from me with regard to the emotional intricacies of two people who are/were in love which in turn has me drifting off and pondering the missteps and misgivings of my own past and present relationships.
