I loved this book because it is so far out there in the zone.  You know about people and different types of personalities, but you just are in awe of them when you actually see it unfold.  Also as you get towards the end you start saying to yourself,""There are really people out there that are really like this."" Maybe to various degrees, but they are out there.  I've ran into a few of them over the years myself.  I can't get away from them fast enough. This book is a psychological study of each of the characters. I couldn't believe the way it twists, then twists again. You are going to be on your toes to the last page.Yes, oh yes, I definitely recommend this book.
Gone Girl is much more than just a cleverly crafted thriller. It is also a hauntingly accurate portrayal of marriage. Sometimes it is so accurate it is upsetting to read. Many readers will probably see bits of themselves in these characters and want to turn away. There are unexpected twists and gotcha moments aplenty, but the real triumph is Flynn's in depth analysis of the marriage of Nick and Amy. You learn of Amy through her diary entries; you learn of Nick through his narration. I don't read a lot of thrillers but this technique seemed original and effective. The story unfolds slowly but the tension never lags. You will be guessing and doubting until the very end!
I bought this book, then I almost didn't read it because I read about how many people hated the ending.  I didn't want to invest my time into a book that had a bad ending, or worse, no ending at all.  So, I reluctantly started reading it when my book club chose it.  Soon, I was enthralled.  And, I think the ending was perfect; I can't think of one that would be better.  Perhaps I enjoyed this book so much because I find psychopathy interesting.  I recently read Ronson's nonfiction book, The Psychopath Test, and this book was a great fictional follow-up.  Well-crafted, clever, insightful, compelling spine-tingler, this novel is original and definitely worth the time!
Well, this was an interesting book. It's hard to say much about it without spoiling the twists and turns (and other reviewers have already mentioned the plot), so I'll just say that the story really picks up in the second part, which is called ""Boy Meets Girl""; this is really the first major twist. From there the story, twists and turns all the way to a rather unusual end--or maybe I should say that the end is more typical of literary fiction, where the good and the bad are gray and people (both good and bad) don't always get what they deserve. I'm going to read this again later this year, I think, just to enjoy the construction of the story all over again.
Overall I really enjoyed the this book. I found it was a good character driven story, but found I was disappointed with the ending. It was almost like the author got to a point and just said ""that's enough"" and ended the story without tying up the loose ends in a way that did not ""fit"" with the main character ""Amy"". If she was as driven to win and punish those who ""wronged"" her, the griffters would have been tracked down and any punished.  And Mrs Collins certainly had the financial means to push for the investigation of the murder of her son...even if these loose ends were tied up in an epilogue, it would have made for a better ending ( for me anyway).
I absolutely loved this book. The characters are not only well developed but they are brand new - nothing recycled here.  The complexities of Amy's personality, the layers of detail, planning and deviousness that were required for her to execute her master plan were fascinating and surprising at every turn, the prose was clear, the language was entertaining and novel. But what struck me most was the dialogue, which was fresh, natural, and rang completely true, a rare find in my reading anyway.  I'm sorry Gillian Flynn is a relatively new author because I know I'm going to go through everything she's written and be left hungry for more.  Perfect book.
