Reading Gone Girl is like strapping yourself into a roller coaster.  The ride starts our slowly, building questions in your mind, as you learn about the characters and their history.  About half way through the roller coaster starts making twists and turns and you won't want to get off until you come to the end. Although this novel is a psychological thriller, it is very well written, smart, and modern. The themes of love, truth, and whether we can ever really know another person, make it so much more than just a thriller. It will keep you guessing.  I read Gone Girl over a 3 day period when it was raining.  I didn't miss being outside at all!
I don't usually read mysteries but was drawn in by the rave reviews and I am so glad I read this.  It's a tough read, from a psychological standpoint, but worth it, because Gillian Flynn is a wonderful writer.  Her characters are richly drawn and she writes beautifully and with humor.  But her stand out quality (at least in this book) is her ability to craft a intricate, clever plot (with twists) with virtually no holes and well-hidden clues.  Equally as impressive is her detailed and fascinating portrayal of a dysfunctional, co-dependent marriage.  I don't want to say more for fear of spoiling the book, but this is definitely worth the read.
