I have not seen the movie, but I cannot see how it will ever do this book justice.  Even if it won an Academy Award for best picture, I am confident people would still say, ""I like the book better.""  Yep, this book is that good...How do you convey onto the big screen the ridiculously good writing?  Little gems like:""I spoke in a soft soothing voice, a voice wearing a cardigan."" - Nick""I gave, and he took and took.  He Giving Treed me out of existence."" - AmyThere were so many, I had to stop writing them down.  And I haven't even gotten to the story itself...hype well-deserved.
An excellent psychological thriller. I particularly liked reading the story in both of the main characters own words.  Amy is certainly psychotic and Nick comes across so real.. and I wanted to shake some sense into him at times!I felt like I was really living both of their stories of the events.  The story unfolded gradually and kept me mesmorised for more details after every read.  I couldn't put it down!A bit disappointed in the ending.  I would have liked to see one of the characters showing some strength without giving it away.A wonderful read.  Will hope that anything else by Gillian Flynn is as good.
I am loving this book.  I watched the movie first and loved it.  I'm not sure which came first, the movie or the book, but they are very similar.  There is very little missing from the movie that I've read in the book, which usually isn't the case.  I haven't made it to the end yet but it seems to be headed in the same direction.  The characters are so great, you find yourself sympathetic with both the husband and the wife at times and at others, you hate them both.  They are both very human, which makes them more believable.  You will be very hard pressed to beat the plot twists in this book.  Overall, an excellent read!
Zowie! The battlefield of marriage has never been more deadly than in Gillian Flynn's latest novel, GONE GIRL.  When perfect wife Amy Dunn disappears from her home under suspicious circumstances, her husband, Nick, well known around his home town as a good guy, is the main suspect.  Amid a media circus that alternatively damns and absolves Nick as the days of Amy absence count down, the story of their marriage slowly unfolds.  Told from the alternating viewpoints of husband and wife, the switchbacks and surprises never let up in this incredibly suspenseful nail-biter. If you're looking for an involving mystery that doesn't hew to bestseller mystery tropes, GONE GIRL is for you.  What a pleasure! Gillian Flynn delivers!
I must admit I was a bit disappointed at the end, but in a way, how else could it end? It was a build up through the whole book and of course you want one or another of the characters to ""win."" When in life does anything have such a neatly wrapped ending? I really enjoyed the book and it is rare for me to find such a page turner. The writing is very good, providing rich detail about the characters whether you like them or not. I feel it deserves five stars for being totally engrossing. It is interesting how many reviewers loved the book but gave it fewer stars simply because they did not like how it ends.
This book is so clever that she had me surprised until the end.  I totally disagree with reviewers who say that she didn't know how to end it.  She knew exactly how to end it -- she did not go with anything expected. The pacing of the book is fantastic and to get readers absorbed in unlikable characters says a lot about the author's craft.There's so little you can say about this book without giving something away, so I will just say that I write fiction and usually read non-fiction because there are few surprises out there.  This book is a gem. I wish I wrote it and Gillian Flynn has a fan for life.
What a bizarre, twisted, crazy book. I feel kind of guilty admitting that I really enjoyed it. Trippy comes to mind. A bad marriage where two people essentially married the fantasy and when the facade started to become transparent, the darkness came. Honestly I think the book is a satire with Flynn thinking ""how can I make this more insane"" and chuckling all the way to the bank. The story was both ridiculous and clever because it does push some buttons in real life relationships. How well do you know your significant other? I thought the story was wicked fun. I finally get what all the hype was about.
