I'm really not much for book clubs.  I tend to like the darker books.  Books not typically chosen in book clubs.  When this was chosen, I actually thought it sounded a bit interesting.  It really was.  The chapters go back and forth between characters.  Those always suck me in.  You really like where one character is heading, know you should be shutting off the lights and going to sleep, yet you plow through three more chapters to find out where this character went next.  While I am no longer in the book club, I'm glad I read this one while I still was!
This is one of the most harrowing reading experiences I have ever had. The main characters tell the story in their own words but they contradict each other and turn out to be unreliable narrators.Nothing is what is appears to be and you never know who to believe. This put me on the edge of my seat throughout the entire book and when it was finished I felt truly horrified.This tale of violence and vengeance will stick with me for a long time.Read it if like scary, psychological novels . . . the ultimate in that genre.
When you want to dive into a new book, what is it you are looking for? Are you looking for a fantasy, with clever archetypes and heroes winning in the end? Are you looking for spiritual fulfillment, a book that lifts the soul and makes you feel better? Or are you looking for a book that gets into you, makes you feel things you may not want to feel, draws feelings and thoughts out of you that you wouldn't dare think otherwise? Are you looking for a book to pass the time? Look elsewhere. Are you looking for a book that cuts you deep? Look no father.
Guys, I'm not kidding around, this book is Everything. Just when you think you know what's going on, the entire story flips around on you and you're like, ""WHAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAT!"" It is a page-turner from the very beginning, and it's incredibly hard to put down. I was depressed when it was over. And because my brain had been pounded into 2014 mush, I was bummed that there were not 2 other books to make it into a trilogy. I would recommend Gone Girl to anyone, and I'd be hard-pressed to find anyone who thought it was weak or boring. READ IT.
Nothing more sweet and satisfying on this earth than a great, original book idea from an author who knows how to unfold her story just the way I like to drink it in ... who snares my interest, sifts through my emotions, wrings out my senses, and steeps me so deeply into her world that I become a [usually!] silent character within it.  This is a must-read from a writer who refuses to bow to the convenient Throne of Banality.  We knew there had to be one out there somewhere, right?  A glorious wordsmith to take up the mantle of early Stephen King?.
This book is not at all what I imagined...it was much better! Gillian Flynn knows a lot about women in relationships. And she knows a lot about character development. I was amazed how at one point during the novel, I was completely sympathetic with Amy, and ten pages later, my feelings had changed in favor of Amy's husband. The book is filled with unimaginable plot twists, and some seriously disturbed characters. I could not put this book down...and I must say it's been years since I've had this much fun reading a book. Brava, Ms. Flynn!
This was an amazing read! My honors English professor assigned this to the class, not only did the whole class love it, but after reading it I bought it for my mom's birthday. While I love to read, this is honestly one of the best books I have ever read. Once you are into part 2, you will forget that Amy and Nick are just characters. During class discussions we would talk as if this was a real story on the news. It is a good read, but not a happily ever after book. Highly recommended and cannot wait for the movie to come out in October.
This is a story of how a fictional marriage which apparently started out with love and happiness slowly becomes a nightmare of attachment due to pressures of economy, family responsibilities and, most importantly, the baggage of youth that each partner brought into the relationship.  We slowly learn each partner's side of the story of downfall through the day-to-day tale of the husband's perspective and what we believe to be the wife's diary during the first half.  Then we learn that both have deceived not only each other, but the reader also.  I couldn't put it down and will most likely read it again.
