Stayed up all night to finish this, then instantly started it again when the kids went to school.  The plot is terrifically entertaining, but read it for the masterful writing--dark, sardonic, and surprisingly funny!  Nick and Amy may not always be nice people, but you have to appreciate their oh-so-snarky, brutally honest insights. I found both characters fascinating and sympathetic (to a point).  Even the minor characters are truly interesting and feel real.  A smart, clever, tricky mindgame of a book.  So much to enjoy here.
Gone Girl is astounding. It is a gripping story of the courtship and marriage of a narcissist and a sociopath who appear to be experiencing the normal setbacks of life during our recent financial meltdown: job loss, relocation, mounting debt, family illness etc. etc. It is easy to identify with them individually which makes it harder to know who to root for when the wife disappears on the morning of their fifth wedding anniversary and the husband becomes the prime suspect. Another astounding read I would recommend is Holding House this will take you on one amazing journey!!!!
Gone Girl is one of the more intriguing mysteries I have read in a while-- well written, keeps you guessing, and very hard to put down.  This novel is a refreshing departure from the tired formula used by most writers--a smart novel that explores the dynamics of a marriage, expectations and how we view ourselves in the context of a relationship. Written in a dueling narrative, we are provided with contrasting viewpoints, which leads the reader to wonder what the truth is. You will keep reading to uncover it. Read this book!
