This is the story about a young married couple, Nick  and Amy Dunne. The wife goes missing on the couples fifth wedding anniversary.  I will not be that specific, since almost everything can be a plot spoiler for this book. It starts out as a typical who done it with the husband as the primary suspect. The husband claims to be innocent and there is no body found as yet, however Nick is just not that upset about his wife's disappearance, and generally behaving inappropriately.Although there will be an answer to whether or not nick killed his wife, this is not a simple murder mystery. This is actually not at all a story about a murder, as others have observed.This is the story of the dissolution of a marriage from first meeting to the ups and downs of marriage and whether a person can ever know who they are marrying.I felt that the authors observations of courtship especially the ""cool Amy"" part was the most insightful thing I have ever read about a woman's behavior when she first meets a man that she is highly attracted to.I also found the bumps in the Dunnes marriage were interesting yet fairly predictable. Again I will not be specific.There are many twists and turns and the reader at times feels like nick is the killer and at times is convinced that he is not.  This book is a major page turner. There are periods in the book where you just have to carry it with you.In particular, I think the ending is astounding and completely unexpected, and highly significant, and once again is acutely insightful about the nature of relationships and what is truly important in life i.e., what individuals value most. I disagree with all those who complained about the ending and there were many. The ending was amazing, fitting for Amazing Amy!I totally recommend this book. It was the most checked out book in the public library for 2012 and lives up to its reputation as a great read and original thriller. It is more a woman's book and has deep psychological overtones and suspense.  my only criticism is that it was a trifle drawn out perhaps at times.
Nick and Amy are a couple who seem perfect on the surface. In Gone Girl, we get a deeper glimpse into their psyches to discover that they are both deeply flawed and perfect “for each other.”Told from the point of view of unreliable narrators, Flynn’s novel keeps the reader guessing and ever in suspense. The novel begins with Amy’s mysterious disappearance on the couple’s fifth anniversary and the chapters alternate between the perspectives of Nick and Amy. Occasionally a chapter will end with a bombshell that made me want to skip ahead to find out what happens next. If you can resist, I wouldn’t recommend skipping ahead more than a few pages to allow the twists and surprises to reveal themselves in due time. This novel made me want to go back and reread sections to see where I was misled.Flynn creates frightening characters and while their motivations are challenging and fascinating to decipher; after reading the entire novel I found their actions were consistent and probable throughout. I did not “enjoy” the ending but found it an appropriate conclusion given what we have learned about Nick and Amy. Flynn doesn’t take the easy route and give the novel the traditionally satisfying ending that the reader may want, but the masterful ending is true to the natures of the characters and their relationship. I don’t think that statement is a spoiler as their true natures are a moving target throughout most of the novel.Gone Girl kept me on the edge of my seat. I was at once captivated and repulsed by the actions of the characters and overall very much enjoyed reading this novel. I would highly recommend it.
After wondering about this book all summer, I bought it as a Christmas gift for my self. I started it reading on Christmas Eve. Christmas day around 10:00pm I was at Part 2 and I couldn't stop after that. I put my kids to sleep and I was up till 1:30am finishing the book and after that horrible ending I couldn't fall asleep. Ms. Flynn ruined my day off with my kids for me...I agree almost every thing people said in the 4 and 5 star reviews but I also agree the 1 stars. Flynn is brilliant. She is a great writer. I wish I had her talent. Great character development, intriguing plot, well-thought, well-written dialogues, good research. (It really shows how much she studied police investigations, ( a lot of CSI), Midwest life, mind of a psychopath) but then comes that horrible ending...After a wonderful thrill ride of 414 pages, comes page 415 and it is awful, terrible, disgusting... a lot of things all at once. Ending ruins the book.May be she wants to write a sequel but again this ending does not fit the book. It puts a big ugly hole into her well thought plot and great writing. Because the ending makes everything she wrote before page 415 unbelievable, if it was this easy to fool us... why ... why ... If I fill in the blanks, it would contain spoilers...So here is my 2 cents after sacrificing my precious sleep to finish this book:I would definitely suggest thriller lovers to read this book. It is one of the best books I've read this year ( and I read quite a few), but may be read up to page 397. Stop there and wait for Gone Girl 2 for the ending to make sense.
