I borrowed this and read it online, so when I thought it was almost over I didn't realize I was only halfway through it. I formed my conclusions, mentally gave it 3 stars and started composing my review in my head while I skimmed through what I thought were the last few pages. I was growing bored, I didn't like the main characters and just wanted to find out where the body had gone to.And then I was whammied. I realized the meat of the book was just starting and it was like coming to the top of a tall roller coaster drop. I couldn't stop reading and it was exciting and I never expected the things that were happening.I thought this was an excellent book and in hindsight I don't even mind how bored I became with the beginning - the information there was necessary and the false expectedness of it really set me up to fully enjoy the last half.I found it to be so well written and the characters seemed like real people. I didn't like the husband and wife because of who they were, not because of how well they were written. So it kind of astounds me that I gave it 5 stars because it's usually very important to me that I like the main character in the book. I didn't really like the ending because it didn't satisfy me but that's just a personal preference. I think it was a very reasonable ending.I keep thinking I didn't like it (I guess because I didn't feel good when I was done reading it) but my strongest thought is wow that is one of the best written novels I've read in a long time.
Now that we know which actors are starring in the film adaptation of Gone Girl, we can reread this novel, wondering how Ben Affleck will stroke his cleft or how Neil Patrick Harris will steal every scene he is in. You'll devour this book, read it quickly, hang onto every word and savor every plot twist (there are many). You'll read it again and again. It's like a breathtaking solar eclipse: beautiful yet dangerous. Flynn writes about the implosion of a marriage between two imperfect people, Amy and Nick, who are perfect for each other. They lie, cheat, steal and they may even kill. But with the organic and addictive way that Flynn writes, you may find yourself saying: ""Oh, that Amy and Nick,the way they talk to each other, that is so (insert your significant other) and me. We are soooo Amy and Nick."" Beautiful, rich, perfect Amy is missing and everybody suspects her handsome, broke and cold husband Nick. Look on your ipad...it's a story that you can see in real life on TMZ or Facebook every minute. But it's more than that. It's the story of a marriage, and the earthquake effects of that relationship on family, friends, the world. On Dateline, the husband's always guilty of murdering his wife. But here, anyone could be guilty with all the layers of motives, emotions, deceit and revenge. Gone Girl is written breezily so you can sail through, letting your stomach lurch at the twists and turns like you're riding the Cyclone roller coaster at Coney Island. Enjoy the ride, and let's hope that the movie lives up to the book.
this was a great read --- I do not see Ben Affleck in the role of the husband - but the movie looks good too - I thought the book was a great read a real page turner - I wanted to go back and read it as each character -
This story was engaging enough to keep me reading when at 45% through (Kindle read), I thought it was all too obvious what the outcome would be and had started getting annoyed with the characters. If the characters start to turn you off, keep reading... there is a fecade happening that catches the reader off guard, and likely not the one you think. This story went from indulging the narratives of two shallow saps to swinging a 180 and revealing unnervingly real people that unfortunately, and eerily, the reader will be able to relate to enough to thank themselves for maintaining sanity where these people allowed themselves to go off the deep end... and it resolves itself in a way that again made me dislike the characters, not relate at all, but believe how they, in all their ego-driven psychosis, ended up at this point.I did find that the writing waffled between surprisingly good and soap-opera-esque.. It doesn't feel fluid in terms of editing. But overall, it's extremely entertaining, utilizes interesting vocabulary, and creates such naked transparent characters out of personalities that everyone has likely encountered, especially in big cities, and are normally never revealed to be constructs/imitations of what is on trend. I loved this plot. This is the first true mystery I've ever encountered that I could easily re-read to garner a new experience. I know the movie is going to have to pick and choose from so much going on here, so I'm excited to see what gets kept and whether they stay true to the ending.
