I rarely assign a rating of five stars, but in this case it is well deserved. The character development and analysis in this book provide depth and believability not often seen in modern fiction. This story is in many ways about the Self, and how it seeks its completion. In this case, Nick is completed by his twin sister, but his new wife Amy can never find completeness since her self image is based on an idealized fictional character named Amazing Amy created by her parents in a popular book series. The book also reveals how we all create personas for ourselves that are often precariously based. In Nick and Amy's case, their personas are based on being writers in a sophisticated New York city crowd. It all comes apart for them both when they lose their writing jobs, their money, and their New York milieu. When they relocate to Nick' s Midwestern hometown to assist his ill parents, the couple's real selves come to the surface, and their marriage turns toxic. Nick begins an affair, and Amy begins her psychotic plotting.Not to reveal spoilers, the actions of both characters could very well seem unbelievable in the hands of a less skilled writer. In Gillian Flynn' s case, she keeps the reader completely involved until the very last sentence. While some readers might have desired a more ""satisfying"" ending to the story, the ending provided is truer to what we could actually expect given the weird circumstances these characters find themselves in.
I woke up early, stayed up late, and snuck off to corners during the day to read a few more pages. Yes, it's good, and a perfect thriller to mow through on a summer's day, and think about for days after.Amy and Nick, a couple young rising New Yorkers, relocate to the Midwest, pulled by family duty and pushed along from the city when they both lose their jobs. Amy goes missing, and mounting evidence suggests Nick was involved. Without giving away too  away, you've got two very unreliable narrators here, and, to me, a couple pretty unlikable characters. Nick's nature and possible secrets come in pieces, and Amy's diary stands in for her side of the story. Add in a trust fund, an affair, and an admirer/stalker from the past, and you've got an ideal modern mystery.Here's what else you get: a slow reveal, a couple switcheroos, and a serves-you-right ending, all told with quick, smart, culturally aware writing that is absolute fun to read.  This book brought to mind the film *Fatal Attraction* from back in the late '80s. Besides being hugely entertaining, that movie served as a cautionary tale for cheating husbands across the country. While before they might have been afraid of being found out; after that movie they were just plain afraid. This book has a similar sense of menace. It might serve as a warning to naughty husbands and wives with roving eyes, especially if it gets made into a movie (fingers crossed).
A neighbor lent me the book, telling me it's even better than the movie, and I was elated to discover a wonderful new writer. Gillian Flynn  has an exquisite sense of language, always inventive, nothing is just plain to her, and she is a very keen observer of life and relationships, all filtered through a first class artistic sensibility. Flynn  is also a great writer about the angst of her generation. This angst reminded me of another book Dream Junkies which was not a thriller, but more a journey of self-discovery, and in the end a little more sweet than bitter, but dealt with this same angst of the post 9/11 years in New York. (It is funny how all this is coming to the surface so much later in contemporary fiction).So the first 30 pages of Gone Girl were love at first sight. As the book advances, it becomes thoroughly heart-wrenching, and perhaps just a little less literary spell-binding, but still excellent. Not sure if the ending is realistic, but this is fiction, and it's all about the idea of things at the end of the day, and the idea was powerful.Gone Girl is a game changer for whoever writes or reads thrillers, because it's so much more than a book just about the page-turner plot, like most of today's popular fiction, say American Psycho, which is also wonderfully written, but lacks soul aka this wounded, real,  universally relatable sensibility, which infuses Gone Girl. Go grab it!
The author has crafted a great story. The style is fast,clean,contemporary.the characters are scary real! Men don't do well in this book. Unfortunately she has many truths about us. An example might be Nick using his female student for lack of mama's adoration.The use of media is very on target. Generally her social commentary is spot on also.I loved that she made sure the reader knew that "" between Boney and me"" is correct grammar! Gillian, you and I agree,but a field linguist will tell you that ship has sailed, prepositions taking the nominative case is now English.I'd be happy to have a cup of coffee with you and commiserate! I loved this book because the author makes us aware of the details of our rather sad culture as when Amy's parents exploit their child for their benefit.The plot is tight. You can't wait to turn the page.I read this book twice.I hated the resolution the first time.However my second read provided a realization that killing Desi was self-defense. You draw your own conclusions whether or not Amy was a sociopath. She makes a pretty good case for what she did.Of course no one wins this battle! How would you like to be their kid! PS I had problems with two names: Go and  Honey. Our cullture usually diminutises names using the first part of a name. Go drove me nuts. And to put a real image in my face ,a honey person,also made me crazy! Nevertheless,read this book. You will have fun and experience quality writing!
With the author narrating the story between alternating first person, makes the book difficult to put down.  Just as one character builds up to a climax, the author switches to the alternate main character!
