Written in the slow and descriptive prose style reminiscent of early Faulkner, the story has surprising twists that unravel with new details revealing characters that are all inherently unlikable.
Allow me to preface by stating I do not read any novels in the genre of crime-thrillers or mystery/suspense, etc. I prefer stories set in alternate, fantastical timelines in which, although people may do hideous things to reach other, is due to this alternate reality. You can't really blame rebels who plot and murder to escape a dystopian society can you?Gone Girl takes me out of this daydream ""comfort zone"" and paints a very believable and hence terrifying picture of domestic bliss gone wrong.  The narrative style was if not unique, brilliant in delivering some of the most introspective, disturbing insights of the human psyche.I now consider this a cautionary tale of gender, marital, and even an individual's societal roles as it affects others.  Are we bring genuine to reach other or just acting out as expected?Gillian Flynn had done an excellent job of pulling the reader through this rollercoaster ride of suspense and intrigue doling out small pieces of a complex plot at a time. Some have stated they did not like the ending but I found it apropo, quite like a tragic French film.Anyone who appreciates a fresh twist in their fiction will enjoy this story.  Then follow it up with something light and fluffy to elevate your psyche up from the chasm into which it had delved in order to sympathize with these characters.
