Without giving any spoilers I'll just say Gone Girl is a psychological joyride. It dissects a marriage between two essentially selfish people Nick and Amy Dunne when Amy turns up missing and Nick is left to a media frenzy as her presumed killer.This book makes you question everyone in your life. I kid you not. These characters are so realistic (albeit insane) they make you wonder if your family could pull off something like this.There are a lot of gender roles that play against the norm. Sexism. A lot of judgemental behavior. A media circus that is entirely realistic.I'm from the great state of Missouri (we'll stick with great, haha) so I was really impressed with how closely the book portrayed my home state. As only a true Missourian could. The Author has to have been here, or come from here. We are all die hard Cards fans, we love the Arch, everyone know the stories written by Mark Twain (Samuel Clemens) and being inside Flynn's book was like walking through the scenery of my life.It doesn't help that my name is Amy. Haha.I would definitely definitely recommend this book to everyone. Of course I had a few friends who said they couldn't get into it. I think because you have to really get into the mindset of this psychological journey. It's a trip.
