When the talented Gillian Flynn puts her name on the cover, you know you are in for a great read, and a well-written ride. Gone Girl does not disappoint. Far from it. The book dissects two people, by having them dissect one another. Here is a story of two people who were ""gone,"" way before Amy, Nick's wife, disappears one day from their home in a small town in Missouri.To reveal how the tale plays itself out would be giving too much away. Amy and Nick are two damaged people. People that are both the product of their upbringing and of their own making, having refused to distance themselves from childhoods that were less than glaringly abusive, but more than simply difficult. They have instead cultivated charming and beautiful exteriors to the delight of all, while nursing jaded and, to one degree or other, ugly interior lives.The book is part murder mystery, part legal mind-bender, and part journal of the disintegration of families, relationships, and some very telling veneer stripping. I look forward to seeing the newly released movie. I hope that what seems on the surface a good cast can do this complex story the justice it deserves, which, ironically, is exactly what none of the characters ever truly get. A very diverting story that will have you squirming as you turn the pages.
Crazy story and an enjoyable read.  I usually don't enjoy books/TV when I can't stand the main characters but this worked.  Great twist and I'm looking forward to the movie coming out.
On the day of Nick and Amy Dunne's fifth wedding anniversary, Amy vanishes -- and all the piling evidence is quickly pointing toward Nick. Even worse, as Nick himself knows, he isn't good at portraying a sympathetic character in his face or mannerisms. Before long, the entire nation is hating him, protesters and reporters crowding his lawn as the police close in on making the arrest.Nick keeps maintaining his innocence -- eventually he comes to believe Amy isn't actually dead at all, and that she's trying to frame him for her murder. Naturally everyone is dubious, having trouble imagining a woman so filled with hate toward her spouse that she'd spend a year plotting the details of a crime rather than simply getting divorced. But Nick knows Amy better than anyone else. Simply put, she's terrifying when she has a vendetta against someone. Her life history has shown this over and over.The story alternates between Nick's and Amy's POVs -- and the reader likewise will keep wondering who is telling the truth, and just where and when.As the book begins, readers may feel they can predict the way the story will go. They are WRONG! This book has multiple twists, right through to the end...which in itself is bound to make you shake your head and really ponder.
I really enjoyed this book from the first page to the last. I enjoyed it so much I was compelled to look up a photo of Ms. Flynn and I do have to say it was like being struck by Cupid's bow if it had somehow been fired out of a cannon.Listen, I don't know if she's married or has a long-time relationship with a same-gender partner and it doesn't matter to me what her lifestyle choices are. I just want her to be happy. I know fame can be difficult and I tasted a little bit of celebrity myself when my college band opened for a little group you may have heard of called, ""The Hooters"" back in 1987. If you don't remember them they had a song called ""And We Danced"" that was a little bit of celtic fusion combined with pure pop dynamism. I played cor anglais and sang backup. But if you ask me my voice was far superior to Randy's. He just couldn't hit the high notes I could.Anyway I digress.I hope Ms. Flynn will read this review and realize that we are probably soul mates and that every minute we spend apart from each other is time wasted. But, Gillian, know that I cannot make the first move, it has to come from you. Look in you heart and I think you will see me there wearing a fez and a ""The Hooters"" concert t-shirt and cargo shorts.Great book.
