I read this book in three days, taking rests only for...ya know...and a few fitful hours of sleep. Also, I think I may have gone partially blind.  How to describe my reading experience?  Okay.  Reading this book was like watching rhinos mate. You want to look away.  You just CAN'T.  Let's see. This book is the literary equivalent of Mr.Toad's Wild Ride. One more. To say Nick and Amy have come to the realization that their marriage sucks is like saying Gregor Samza woke up one morning and realized he was going to have a baaaaad day.The book is fabulous, end to end. I know some people are disappointed with the ending--and I wasn't exactly doing cartwheels, either. But, after further thought, I understood that it had to end the way it did. Anything else would have been trite. The writing was smooth, refreshing, seamless. What a relief to read a book without being distracted by bad writing. Ms. Flynn sure knows how to whirl a baton.I loved it. Every word of it. The book was creepy, astonishing, devious. At some points, it made me feel backed into a corner with no place to run. This is not a crime novel. It's a novel about two people short circuiting. It's about love, and love that never was.Get it. Read it.
I live in Missouri, Was raised in Missouri....And we are the show me state. We love to show off..... However, Gillian took ""show me"" to ""holy s***"". This was the best book I've ever read, and trust me, I've read a lot. This book had me guessing till the end, never expecting what was waiting around the corner. It's what my highschool English teacher calls a ""tough"" read, in the sense that it has some big words that young teens like myself might find hard to... Get. There so much sex in this book, it might blow your mind, however it never stopped me from reading it. The author tells both sides of the story so you fully understand both brains of the couple. Near the end my brain was getting fuzzy (that might just be because it's midnight here and I'm choosing to write about this book instead of sleep on a school night.... Why?) Because this book was that AMAZING(inside joke)! So I have a little message to Gillian, ""you changed the way I see society, the way I see cop shows and murders. What you did was truly amazing. Heck, I read this on my kindle, I highlighted several things in this book. Things that will keep me afloat. (I swear the whole book is highlighted)! What I'm trying to say is your a genius and your book deserves 5 stars.
I came to this book without expectations. It seems everyone but I had heard of it and already added it to their Goodreads ""Want to Read"" bookshelf, but it's all in character for me, so I shouldn't be surprised. That being said, I only got to page 16 before I decided I loved this book. Gillian (like my name, so we're practically twins!) Flynn's Gone Girl is a perfect specimen for a morbid curiosity. The girl in question is Amy Elliott Dunne, the supposed victim in a missing person's case. Her husband Lance Nicholas ""Nick"" Dunne is the supposed perpetrator (because it's always the husband, right?). Amy and Nick are beautiful, successful, clever, and bursting with love for each other, but when both are laid off, the initial spark of their marriage dies out, and a family crisis uproots them from their beloved Manhattan and lands them in Nick's rural Missouri hometown of North Carthage, the two are embroiled in a battle of wit, sadism, and manipulation. You won't be able to tear your eyes away from this train wreck, and you may think you can predict the outcome (and maybe you're better at that than I am), but you will enjoy the unfolding of this disastrous relationship the whole time.Read the rest of my review on my blog: [...]
