This book surprised me. I had already seen the movie trailer which piqued my interest but I had no idea what a strange sociopathic hell was awaiting behind the cover. This story very easily could have been contrived and messy but I didn't find it to be at all. It was precision madness. Every time I thought, ""Perhaps now things will even out,"" some fresh disaster was unleashed on our less than likeable main character, Nick. Surprisingly, at no point did I have the urge to jump ahead...I was content to let the story unfold. I know people who hated the ending but I thought it was a masterful stroke. This was not a happy ending kind of story, not in the romantic sense but I found it poignant and fitting that these two would find themselves so entangled as to not be able to be without the other because, yes, I am convinced it was more than just the baby for Nick. He was both victim and sidekick to Amy's nightmarish ego both feeding off of and fearing her at the same time and rightly so. So...well done. I don't know if this makes any sort of difference but this is the first book, the first anything, I have been compelled to review on Amazon and I have been a customer for years. Enjoy
