I went through this book pretty quickly because it was so good. If you think you know what will happen at any point, guess again. Very well written and entertaining.
I haven't really read many thrillers - if that's even what you'd call Gillian Flynn's ""Gone Girl."" Flynn's breakthrough novel, the one which thrust her into national spotlight, tells the story of the tragic, troubled marriage of Nick and Amy Dunne. Both writers, (Nick recently lost a job writing for New York magazines, Amy used to write puzzles for magazines, with dwindling income) Nick and Amy move back to Nick's small midwestern hometown to help care for Nick's ailing mother. The perfect couple - at least at first glance - their marriage seems to unravel as the story progresses. Told from alternating viewpoints: Nick in first-person present narrative, while Amy's story is heard in flashbacks via excerpts from her diary. Nick seems insincere as the case against him tightens, but is he really guilty? Or is there more to the story? Told with wonderfully athletic prose and witty turns of phrase, the author pulls you in and whispers ""Hold on..."" as the safety bar cinches down across your lap and you head for the first drop of her roller-coaster ride of a novel. A wonderfully suspenseful read, Gillian Flynn takes us to some Dark Places, indeed.
Normally, when a best-selling novel is developed into a movie, I prefer to read the novel first. However, this time around, I am ashamed to admit that did not happen. Once the film was in theaters, my boyfriend and I went to see it. (Okay, I pretty much dragged him there). By the end of the movie, I was baffled in the outcome and wished that I had indeed read first and then watched. The thing is, although I do own a Kindle Fire (at the time I owned a NOOK), I hate to purchase books, and instead will borrow them from the library. I had Gone Girl on hold for what seemed like forever. Finally, it was my turn to borrow the ebook. I immediately began reading and I soon was aware of just how well the movie actually followed the book. I can only remember one other time I read a book, which eventually made it to the big scree, and perfectly followed the book. Nothing upsets me more than when I read a book, to later watch the film and see all the changes that were made. This to me completely takes away from the novel's purpose inspiring the motion picture to begin with. If you have seen the film and not read the book, I highly recommend you pick up your copy asap.
