Wow. This book was so incredibly well written. Details were the crux of the storyline. Amy was so incredibly brilliant but damaged at the same time. How the daughter of 2 psychologists could operate the way she did is puzzling and at the same time revealing. It seems they were her early enablers. Amazing Amy led the perfect life while daughter Amy existed is the part the parents were responsible for. How could they not see how Amy would feel inferior even if she didnt verbalize it to them?I love the ""cool girl"" references. Nick and Go have their twindom that seems authentic. Nick and Amy both seem so likeable at the beginning when they are speaking their truths to us. Telling us what they wanted us to know about them; and then they stopped pretending and showed us who they really were. You honestly didn't predict anything that happened because unless you're an honest to God psycho yourself, you couldn't have.The fickleness of the media and public perception with criminal cases was spot on. Highly recommend!
This is the sort of book you have trouble leaving, no matter how urgent the demands of living your own life are.  While I spent a lot of my reading time thinking, ""Noooo!"", I expected it to come out all right in the end.  My eldest son would love the ending.  But I am dissatisfied that a vicious sociopath will be raising another human being.  I also want the Ozark ironic robbers back on the scene, Go and Boney happy that Amy is locked away or dead.  At the very least I want Go to have Nick' s book on a memory stick and all the stuff in Go's shed sold on EBay.  I know that life is not fair, but I like my fiction to be, at least a little.  That's probably one of the reasons this book is so good.  Of course it's well written but Flynn has the courage to leave the monster in place and the monster in Nick forever blackmailed into submission by the advent of a son.  Not every sociopath can have a Hitleresque blow out suicide, leaving his pet psychopaths flapping in the wind.  Amy is no Madeline, which should make many readers happy, but not me.
well, i was going to write a full blown review, but i don't have the time or energy for it now, so i'll just give a shorthand version of my what was going to be a full fledged review.......this book is great!! i don't mean dostoyevsky, f. scott fitzgerald, hemingway type of great. no offense to the writer. i mean great concept/plot, great way to reveal or not reveal writing & best of all, you LITERALLY DID NOT WANT TO (& COULDN'T) PUT IT DOWN!!i can normally predict plots, how they will go, what the outcome will be, etc. & w/this, i DID also have predictions, but she twisted & turned a bit beyond my predictions & i was THRILLED w/what she did w/this story. i had been wanting to see the film badly, but then decided if i saw the film, i would not want to read the book, as it would be ""ruined"" for me. at least if i read the story first & know it, the film can still be enjoyed, even though i know what is coming. so i HIGHLY recommend this book: as a great story, as a page turned, and as a good amount of a mind blower! :)
