Is it just me or is this book genius? I've read Gillian Flynn's two other books and this one had a completely different vibe than them. At first it's a game of loving husband and wife, but as the story unfolds you see a world of lies created. I'll say, it wasn't until about halfway through the book when I started to perk up and really wonder about what was going on, but I think that's the point of the book. Flynn was able to completely take me along for the ride. She really makes you choose teams between husband and wife, and then she reveals bits and pieces little by little. I am just amazed at the complexity of this book and her characters.And for those complaining about the ending (and without spoiling it), in my opinion, it was the only plausible ending I could see, considering all that had happened.So I think overall, this is a great book that keeps you thinking. I've officially turned into a fan of Flynn's and am anxiously awaiting another story from her.
I resisted reading this book, purely because it was so incredibly popular. I didn't have high expectations of it. But a friend of mine encouraged me to pick it up, and I am so glad I did. I couldn't put it down. I raced through it, and enjoyed every minute of it.Gone Girl is primarily about marriage, and the way men and women communicate before and after marrying. It is told from the perspectives of both the husband, Nick, and the wife, Amy. The first third of the book brought up a lot of emotion for me, because the character development was so true and reminded me of some of my past relationships. The second third is where the story begins to twist, and nothing is sure. And in the last third, the story simply snowballs into a spectacular and suspenseful tale. I don't want to give details that will spoil the mystery for readers, but just know that you will be riveted.This was a terrific summer read, and I highly recommend it to men and women alike.
Strap in, put your head back, relax and admire the climb up to the initial view of the honey soaked lives of newly married New York City it girl and hunky mid-western boy.  But get ready, hold onto your stomach and brace yourself for a dizzying crazy plunge down with Gillian Flynn's Gone Girl.First you cheer for wife Amy, ""fat with love"" for her new husband, removed from her job, her brownstone in the city, her childhood inheritance and relocated to a small Missouri town.  Then loopback, rooting for Scotch soaked Nick, cheating husband, worn down from Amy's insatiable need for worship and admiration.Accelerating through the turns of a marriage spiraling out of control; deception, scorn, adultery, resentment, cunning revenge, and eventually murder.  Ending after the final tunnel, ruined careers, scattered bodies, and an unexpected pregnancy. The mystery stops, eerily returning the readers and Amy and Nick to a similar spot from which the ride began.
Don't read reviews, just buy the book and dive in. There's just too much in this novel that could be ruined, and what a loss that would be for the reader. So I won't even allude to any twists, I will simply recommend this book and give it 5 stars bc I can't give it 10.This was my first Gillian Flynn novel (her 3rd), so I immediately read her other two. While they were all wonderful, Gone Girl is definitely her masterpiece. In GG, her writing ability caught up with her devilishly clever ideas. Her second novel ""Dark Places"" is built around a genius idea (the ""kill club"" element), but doesn't quite have the tight pacing of Gone Girl, which is flawless.Now that I've finished all of her books, I'm not sure what to read next! It's always hard to follow a great book. I'll spend the first few chapters of whatever I read next feeling annoyed that Gone Girl is all gone (,girl!).Until the movie, that is. GF is writing the screenplay as I write this review. Fun!!!
One of the best thrillers ever. It is only once every few years when one comes across a potboiler tale so well written, complete and continuously surprising.Unlike the normal crime stories, the book builds slowly; and this is another positive. As the suspense builds to a potential climax with the remaining half of the book looking like turning in to something totally run of the mill, the unexpected erupts to change the landscape. As the reader fears again surge towards an expected retribution tale with a quarter of the book remaining, the book continues to take unexpected turns towards an unexpected end.Apart from the clever story and foxing the readers again and again, the author must be commended for keeping it real, credible, tight and constantly flowing. If it was not a regular crime story, the book could have been in contention for many serious awards too. The author might not be unhappy with all the book and potential movie revenues though.
Even grouchy old white guys like your humble reviewer relished the many delights to be found in Gillian Flynn's runaway bestseller and A list movie with Ben Affleck! If only Miss Flynn had lived at the same time of Alfred Hitchcock the famous suspense  genius and the young female author could have made quite a team.  the Plot concerns the disappearance of a brilliant, orderly and obsessive young woman named Amy. The event takes place on she and her husband Nick's fifth wedding anniversary. The couple had left their swanky New York milieu for the wilds of New Carthage Missouri in order for Nick to care for his ailing parents. Did Nick kill Amy? Is Amy really alive seeking to torture Nick? The plot has as many twists and turns as the labyrinth of Greek mythology. Nick and Amy are both well educated magazine writers. Flynn is adept at dropping allusions to popular culture. The book is much better than I thought it would be.  Read it and you will become a Flynn fan.
A friend of mine said this book was a ""page turner"" and she was so right.  I was spending alot of time at the hospital after my significant other was in a serious car accident and I needed a book that would catch my interest from the start. I loved the convenience of quickly downloading the book to my Kindle and I was hooked from page one.  You'll love the twists the author incorporates throughout the book and how she intertwines humor with suspense.  I guarantee you won't be disappointed.  As soon as I finished ""Gone Girl"", I quickly downloaded another book by the same author, Gillian Flynn.  I love her style of writing.  I can't tell you how many books I've started to read and lost interest...but I couldn't wait to get back to reading this book to see what would happen next.  Part of me actually didn't want to finish it because I didn't want it to end.  I felt like I knew the characters because they were so well developed.  Read it for yourself and see if you agree.
Gillian Flynn writes an amazing book on the struggle between the life of a husband and his psychotic wife. On the day of their five year anniversary Amy, the wife, fakes her disappearance and attempts to frame her own husband for the murder. She is sneaky in the way that he would have lots of motive to kill her because of money. However, this is not the case, even though they are facing hardships in their relationship, Nick would never do such an act. When he finally realizes that his wife is in fact crazy, it is too late and he is unable to get out of the relationship. The book was filled with lots of thrill. It constantly threw different twist into the plot to keep the reader entertained. I would recommend this book to anyone, but more specifically the young adult. It is too inappropriate for the young reader and would make any of your grandparents’ ears fold over. That does not mean though that it is not just the perfect amount of drama, excitement, and curiosity.
Wow! These two characters are exactly that, crazy! It's no wonder the dude cracks up because she is a crazy woman!! Couldn't put it down
There are so many plot twists and turns that you will feel like you are spinning! Very well written. I would highly recommend this book!
I am so confused.  I loved it, I hated it, it was BRILLIANT with a capital B and disappointing {lowercase d}.  This author does magic with words.  The story line is bleak, and yet-as the reader you enjoy every bit, it is FUN, it is witty. Witty is the best adjective for the book.  So, why hate it a tad?  Because it's pathetic, dark, psychotic.  The ending leaves you a little empty- you wanted a smooth, big pink bow and the whole thing wrapped up tidily.  At the same time you know- there could not have been another ending, really.  You didn't like it, but that's how it is.  The twists, the ""I like her, oh wait! I hate her...okay maybe I like her again..."" was all leading up to a big bowl of hollowness. Brilliant, engaging, someofthebestmostinterestingwritingever. Seriously, the author is phenomenal. The first 2/3 of the book- 5 gigantic stars.  the last 1/3-  2 stars{but a valid ending...I'm just a whiney romantic}.  warning- there is some especially crude language.
I cheat when I read mysteries; I can't lie. I'm one of those ""reads the last page"" readers - which is tough in an age of digital books.  So I read reviews and looked up spoilers (of which there weren't any tell-alls that I found), but I knew that LOTS of people really hated the ending of this book.I was prepared for that.When I got to the end, I understood why people hated the ending, but I wasn't one of them, actually. I thought both characters are pretty are awful people, and I don't care for them AT ALL, but I really liked how Flynn worked it all in and pulled together an ending I didn't anticipate. I'm still thinking about it, which, for me, is a marker of a great book - when the characters stay with you for days/ weeks after you've read it, teasing apart the strands of the story to investigate the deeper underlying themes. For that reason, I gotta give it five stars: I'm still unravelling themes and motifs and realities from Gone Girl.
Amy and Nick's 5the wedding anniversary is now, and all seems happy and well that morning, until Nick comes back home after a neighbor's phone call claiming the front door is open and their cat is setting on the front steps. Nick finds the house in shambles, and signs of a struggle. He calls the police and his nightmare begins. Amy is the ""Amazing Amy"" from the books her parents have written, and Nick is the ""boy-next-door"" perfect husband. How could anyone accuse Nick of even hurting his wife? The book goes back and forth with each characters perspective. Two psychotic people in a controlled and manipulated marriage brings a creepy, bizarre, terrifying and page turner book. This is the most brilliant piece of work I have read yet this year. It will no doubt be my favorite 2013 read. I can't wait to read more of her work. Adult situations and language. What an amazing book to read. I just couldn't put it down and get it out of my head for days. 100 stars for me.
Fascinating characters and many turns and twists in this riveting book.  This author deserves kudos for such an original plot.
What a total mind game...  It kept me coming back for more though!  Disturbing and brilliant.  I honestly could not put this book down.
