I had such conflicting emotions and loyalties reading this book. I am trying to figure out the best way to word this review without giving anything away. I loved the mystery and the way the author had you think. You knew what was going on, only to find out you didn't. This book really makes you think. Yes I know I'm repeating myself.It's not a beach read where you can set the book aside, go splash around in the ocean and then pick it back up. You want to finish it, now. I almost gave this a four star because of the ending. Then I thought no, when I really thought about the two characters and the history of their personalities and conflict, the author really couldn't end it any other way. Or either Amy or Nick would have been out of character. I know that doesn't make sense, and maybe after you read it, it still won't. But for me, though I was disappointed in the ending, I loved this book and it really couldn't end the way I wanted it to.
Gone Girl deservers every bit of praise I am about to bestow on it. As an English teacher, I am always looking for a good book (one I cannot put down) that can also stand on its own in a literary sense. I had begun to grow used to sacrificing quality for thrill (think The Di Vinci Code or anything Steve Barry), but with Gone Girl, this is just not the case. Flynn weaves an enthralling story of betrayal and deception, with literary elements to rival some of the best. I would find myself taking pause to think about how this author had twisted my stomach in such knots, feverishly flipping pages on my Kindle. Steer clear if you need a good night's sleep or you want to continue to view your spouse in the same way (I have to admit, I drilled my husband a few times and after reading you will understand why). Gone Girl does contain some ""colorful"" language and I would not recommend it to the faint of heart. Nicholas Sparks fans detour away from Gone Girl.
