I'm surprised to see so many complaints about this book's ending. Did you expect a neat, tied-in-a-bow ending? Did you expect to be satisfied? I can almost hear Amy and Nick laughing at you.As this novel progresses, you'll feel manipulated, deceived, betrayed... Isn't that what an unraveling marriage does to a person? Instead of just telling about it, Gillian Flynn decides to take you along. Ms. Flynn remains true to the end, leaving you flipping back and forth between the last page and the acknowledgements, your brows knit, asking, ""Really? That's the ending?""No, you won't feel good when this novel ends. You won't feel satisfied or justified. You'll feel like a thorn has been inserted just beneath the surface of your skin: it won't really hurt, but it will itch and burn, and you'll feel it. And think about it.I love that I hated the book. Ms. Flynn wanted to provoke, to needle; and she does it brilliantly.
