Let it be clear: there's a reason David Fincher became attached to the film adaptation of this book. The man isn't exactly known for films with lovable characters and heartwarming endings...This book is a contemporary classic, with all the requisite intrigue and page-turning suspense of a modern-day thriller, but character depth and literary skill attributed to masters of the craft. Well-drawn, morally ambiguous characters, and excellent twists and reversals (which may not all be completely unexpected, but are nonetheless effective) draw you deeper and deeper into the world of greys Flynn has created.This isn't the type of story that will appeal to everyone, though. There are no heroes here, no plucky underdogs to root for, and no easy resolutions. If you don't care for ambivalence like this, you may want to stay away. For others, this is an experience that will stay with you days after reading. Not to be missed.
Book better than the movie, but the movie was not bad.  Read the book first and you will enjoy the movie better.  I am surprised how much I liked this book.  It is a dark book but it works and kept me interested and curious.  I liked that both characters are flawed and I was not sure what is going on until deep into the book.  I thought the book to be well written. The author is very good and painting a scene with out the boring details.  At one point she describes children following their mother through the crowd like kites.  This has hardly anything to do with the story, but the images it brings to mind worked for me, enough that I still remember it.  I know that the author was not the first one to compare children to kites, that was not the point.  The book was well done, complex enough to interest, but not so technical that it confusticates the reader, in this case me.  I am definitely going to read more of Gillian Flynn's novels.
I enjoyed reading this book.  I don't need to summarize the book for you, other reviewers have already done that.  What I can say, is you will enjoy this book and will appreciate the superb writing of Ms. Flynn.  The book takes you from present day Missouri to when the characters meet in New York and why they were in Missouri on that day of their fifth wedding anniversary  when Amy disappeared,  When a writer grabs you and holds you to the very last page and you completely relate to the characters, I consider that to be a good book.I admired the character Amy (Nick's wife).  I really did.  Ms. Flynn made her so very good at being bad, the admiration for her character is expected.  Nick, her husband was trying too hard to be liked, he could not live his life, while Amy was observant and smart and devious.  Would not want to spoil the book if you have not yet read it, but this is one of the best books I have read in a while.
having read raving reviews about this novel I decided to buy it for my Kindle. I was at first hesitant since so MANY people wrote negatively about the ending. However, I was NOT disappointed in the book! It is cleverly written and has a great story line. It contains so many observation about men and women; those felt like extra side notes to the main plot. It reads very well and keeps you interested enough by revealing the plot in small doses so you don't feel like you need to skip to the ending while, in the process of skipping, missing all the small twists and turns, and entertaining observations, along the way.As for the ending - i thought it was fitting even though not explosive finale. That's how people are and most things in life end in an ordinary (as opposed to Hollywood-like) fashion. Although, i would not call the ending ordinary. It was a weird resolution to which many people would not agree (had it happened to them).
