What do women really want from men?What do men really want from women?Gillian Flynn frames her multi-layered mystery thriller, GONE GIRL, around these fundamental questions. The premise is that what we believe will affect our relationships --- and ultimately our individual identities.The architectural plotting of this noir novel, with its curves, carvings, and fine detail will satisfy readers who love a fast-paced storyline. Flynn offers us far more. Even though the generous use of clipped sentences speed you, slow down to more fully appreciate the complex characterizations and literary devices, the integration of back story to build suspense, the oh-so-visual descriptions of the numerous settings, and the garden maze of truth and lies. Such a rich read!Best sellers rarely make my reading list. Serendipity brought me a used copy. All I can say to summarize is: Thank you Gillian Flynn!
I'm giving this book 5 * based on it's ability to keep me distracted during the train journey from hell. I bought the book at a station, little suspecting I would need it to sustain me during a journey that should have taken 50 minutes but ended up taking 6 hours.This book is a page turner. It's difficult to write a review without spoilers but needless to say I had my own idea about Amy's disappearance (which turned out to be wrong).What I really liked was that both lead characters were so deeply flawed that they turned out deserving one another - no mean feat for a writer. I wouldn't like either Amy or Nick in real life, but could totally see how they would take people in and deceive them. That one character was played by the other only heightened their basic emotional dishonesty and made one seem worse than the other, rather than one a victim and one the aggressor.A clever book that is a great distraction.
I was impressed every minute I was reading this book and enjoyed almost all of it: I was pretty uncomfortable throughout the last chapters, but that's another compliment: that a book can create a response so powerful in me.I think it was an incredible book, even though the actual story was INSANE!  The way the themes of the book wove in and out of the social landscape of our decade was masterful: Job Loss, a ghost town created by the 2008 economy crash, the way the media exploits these types of stories.  There is just so much there that tells the ""American Story"" of today.  I couldn't be more impressed. The commentary on relationships today was scarily insightful; not the main relationship, of course, which was what I would call 'something else', but the courting process and how we draw each other in was apt.I recommend this book to anyone with a strong stomach for raw emotion and explicit language and situations.
This is one of those rare occurrences in which the hype is justified. While I’m not a regular reader of novels in the suspense/thriller genre, I decided to give this one a try after hearing about the mind-bending plot twist, and wanting to be in the know before the film version is released next year.And ‘Gone Girl’ surpassed my expectations. Gillian Flynn’s prose is easy-to-read yet smart and witty. In the beginning, I thought the chapters corresponding to Amy’s PoV were a little pretentious and clunky. Thankfully, you realize midway through the novel that this was done on purpose (no spoilers).I know a lot of people were upset with the ending but I thought it was perfect. I read that Gillian Flynn was influenced by “Rosemary’s Baby” in the writing of this novel and this is most evident in the ambivalent ending, which like real life, shows that one may never really rid themselves of our lives’ demons.
Book #41 Read in 2013Gone Girl by Gillian FlynnI do not think I have ever read a book that had as main characters such unlikable people as this book did; Nick and Amy are nasty.  That being said, this book was like a train wreck and I could not look away; I had to keep reading to find out what happened.  On their fifth wedding anniversary, Amy goes missing.  Shortly thereafter, the police and the media are looking at Nick as the person who made Amy disappear.  He had cheated on her, emotionally withdrawn from her and, according to Amy's found diary, physically abused her at times.  But did Nick really kill her?This book had tons of twists and turns to keep readers engaged.  I was rooting for both Nick and Amy to get their just desserts.  This was a good mystery and I recommend it.  It seems to be one of those books that people either love or hate; I was more on the love side.[...]
