Once a novel is adapted to film people run out to find the source material. I try not to be that guy but in this case I was. And I'm a better reader for it.I actually purchased the prose a week before the film was released on bluray. I had heard nothing but good things about the film and I wanted to read the book before watching the movie. It was a great choice. It gave so many layers to the story that didn't make it into the film and explained the mindset in ways that made you empathize with the players more.It's one of the best novels I've ever read. I'm the kind of guy who likes prose to have layers. To be a quick, easy read on the surface but to have more to if you really think about what's occuring. I like to feel like the writer has the protagonist speaking directly to the audience. The writer has accomplished this in spades. I can't wait to read more of her stuff!
Where do I even start with this book? I love Gillian Flynn's writing. I picked up Sharp Objects at first, and then Dark Places. I was hesitant to read Gone Girl, just because there was a movie coming out and I wasn't sure if it was my cup of tea. Boy, was I wrong. After reading the story of Nick and Amy, I was left slack-jawed and unsure what the hell had just happened. To make a potentially long review, short, Flynn creates dynamic characters that you love to hate, and hate to love. The more you learn about each party, the more you find yourself wondering who's side you're on. Who is right and who is wrong? Amy and Nick are dynamic and human. They are people you run into but don't know the depths of who they are. These are people who we know on a first name basis, but never question their motives. Bravo, Ms. Flynn. It's not often that I wan't to throw a book but keep reading at the same time.
