Gillian Flynn is a true genius. Filled with heart-pounding twists and turns, her masterpiece Gone Girl never ceases to disappoint. Utilizing a dueling narrative structure between Lance ""Nick"" Dunne and his missing wife Amy, Flynn successfully creates two entirely engrossing characters. Each tells their version of events with such a lively tone that even when dealing with such dark subject matter, I still found myself chuckling several times throughout.This is a true examination of the human psyche, delving into some of the darkest parts of the mind and exploring how love can quickly turn from pure and innocent to unclean and dangerous. Every move made by her characters has been meticulously researched. Flynn's novel is one worth reading multiple times so as to truly understand each character even more.I highly recommend this. Read this before seeing the movie.
Gone Girl is the story of Nick and Amy, a highly dysfunctional New York City couple who relocate to Nick's hometown in Missouri to care for his ailing parents.  Nick comes home one day to their ""mcmansion on the river"" to find his living room in a shambles and his wife gone.  The story is told through the alternating perspectives of Nick and Amy, going all the way back to the time they met up to present day.  I became a Gillian Flynn fan after reading Sharp Objects, and Gone Girl did not disappoint.  After reading these two books, I'm going to start calling her the Queen of F***ed Up Characters.  Her writing is crisp, clean and vivid, some of her prose reading like poetry.  After getting to know the characters through their history, the ending did not surprise me, but it also did not disappoint.  My recommendation would be to sit back and enjoy the ride and thank God for your own normalcy.
This novel was a book club selection and I purchased it knowing only that a wife was missing and her husband was the prime suspect in her likely death.  This was also my first experience reading Gillian Flynn.  What a wonderful, but disturbing ride!  I couldn't put it down!  And, I would definitely recommend it. I really enjoyed how the story unfolded and the pace she kept as she alternated the narration between husband and wife and provided readers with an understanding of both perspectives!  When we do hold our discussion, I think there are many areas to explore.  My short list includes:  (1) What are the values that this couple holds dear?  And, how do those values affect how the author chose to end her story?  Some aspects were extreme enough to WANT to discuss further, but one can simply enjoy it for the pure entertainment value of a good mystery!  I plan to read her other two novels.
BLUF: Great story with a poor ending.The premise of this book is pretty simple. Wife goes missing. Husband didn't do it. Police think he did. It's an irresistible storyline.Which is why you will keep reading even after you realize that the husband is a dope, the wife is likeable but socially ridiculous, and that the story continues despite having nothing interesting to share......but then there is a twist. It's wonderful. Even though you don't care about the players, you cannot put this book down. Sorry for the cliche, but it's like watching a car wreck - you just cannot look away, for better or worse.Which is fortunate because, while it gets better, the ending is not satisfying.The reason I marked this as a recommended title is because I couldn't stop talking to people about this book after the twist. I rarely share like this.
Gone Girl is the third novel by American author, Gillian Flynn. ""She was the girl that every girl wanted to be: beautiful, brilliant, inspiring and very wealthy. He was the guy that all men admired: handsome, funny, bright and charming. But on July fifth, their seemingly perfect world came crashing in when Amy Elliott Dunne disappeared on their fifth wedding anniversary."" Flynn alternates narrations from husband Nick Dunne starting the day of the disappearance with diary entries by Amy Elliott Dunne starting when she first met Nick, and later, narrations by Amy, to gradually lead the reader through a tense, clever plot with some breathtaking twists and turns. Along the way, she touches on the power of TV and social media, the influence of good (and bad) parenting and whether anyone can really know their spouse. With plenty of black humour, Gone Girl is witty, scary, funny and brilliant.
