As so many others, I am not sure that I like the ending. It's fatalistic, and crazy, to think that this marriage will go anywhere, other than maybe spawn a screwed-up child, or two, and one spouse will kill the other eventually.I would have liked the ending to be, for Nick and Amy, both, to adhere to their inherently bad (insecure ?) characters, and unite them in a different way.I was somehow expecting, that there would be another twist, and that they both were targeting, and craving Desi's money and lifestyle together. And that the whole last plot was, Amy, infiltrating Desi's life after so many years again (with Nick's consent), trying to get hold of the lake-place, and all other assets he had.But that would have meant another turnaround in the main character's bevaviour.$Guess, I have to write my own book, with 'my' ending.Great read, though!!!
What I enjoyed most about this book was the wonderful prose.  As I was reading it, over and over I wanted to stop and read a passage out loud to my wife.  The author had some amazing lines and paragraphs, beautiful and insightful writing.I also love twists, and this book threw one twist after another at the reader.  Many times I sat up and said, ""Wow!""The development of characters was also amazing.  The author digs deep into personality of characters.  The characters are drawn in exquisite detail and, though dysfunctional in the extreme, still believable.Many reviewers disliked the end, and I have to say that this was my exact reaction at the time.  I got to the end and just said, ""Huh?  That's it?""  But on reflection I realize that it really was a great ending, both realistic and ironic.  It just takes some time to sink in.
The manipulation, never knowing what horrible thing will happen next, making nice out of total fear, no one really believing you, even you doubting yourself at times, what truth is the real truth?...It sounds so preposterous, and yet...!! I believe at least 75% of people are dual personalities...not schizophrenic or the mentally ill, but normal (whatever we perceive that to be for us) everyday people like you and me (correct grammar)...one public personality and one private one that generally only appears with family,  who love you unconditionally, or so we say and want to believe...This book does an excellent job of telling a story that goes to the utmost extremes of pretty much every normal human emotions...really enjoyed reading it, seeing the movie tomorrow, I always like to read the book first....I can't wait to see it!!  This is definitely a book everyone should read...
