This lives up to the hype, it really does. The relationship between the husband and wife is dynamic, twisted, and fascinating. You can truly feel the tension and dislike between them as you read, and it makes for a great story. The concept is brilliant and Gillian Flynn deserves the attention she got for writing this. I wasn't crazy about the journal entry chapters initially, but once I got going, it really made the entire story flow with the different perspectives.If you liked this book and other similar ones, you may very well like my first novel, DECEPTION. Although definitely not the same concept, the relationships in it do play out similarly if that interested you in GONE GIRL. The ending isn't the best, but it does make you think...what happens now? Definitely a surprise though.
Hell hath no fury like a woman scorned... This is one helluva twisted story about a self-righteous, vindictive, psycho bitch! I flipped-flopped back and forth through out the entire book whom I should hate more. I hated Nick for his infidelity (I am of the variety that believe NO reason is a reason to cheat). Then, I got the grand shock that Amy played all of us! She is a master manipulator and could scheme like no other. At that point, I was pissed but still wanted to explore the twists and turns of Amy's sociopathic brain. I feel the ending was rather anti-climatic; the ultimate shock happened in the middle of the book. The writing was excellent with a great look inside both character's behaviors and thinking, beating that each character were totally different. Or were they? The book definitely left me thinking about the big what ifs and did this mean that? and so on.
Gillian Flynn knows how to take you gently by the hand and then heave you over the precipice.  Often I thought I had this story figured out, only to have it twist and turn and leave me fooled right up to the very end.  ""Gone Girl"" will have you up all night reading until your eyes smart.  Have a bottle of Visine handy, you will need it.As in Ms. Flynn's previous two novels, the main characters in this one, husband and wife, Nick and Amy Dunne have secrets.  The story is told in real time from the viewpoint of Nick and through the diary of Amy.  I don't want to give away anything that happens beyond the first section of the book as this would spoil it for new readers, but be forewarned that when you've finished the book you might want to turn back to page one to start it all over again.
