This was a fast, engaging read. I hated having to put it down, and every time I did, I kept thinking about it. I don't often agree with all the hype that people dump on certain books or movies, but this one didn't disappoint. I can see why it has become such a sensation.I've read a few of Gillian Flynn's other books, and I think Gone Girl is my favorite. She's a brilliant, entertaining writer. You can tell that she puts a lot of thought into her storylines, weaving each thread just so into the intricate web of deceit and horror that keeps these stories going.What else can I say about Gone Girl? If you're read her work before and liked it, then this is another one to pick up. If you're new to her work, this would be a great story to start on. I'll definitely keep watch for her next book.Run, don't walk, to get your copy.
I'm glad I read the book before I watch the movie (very excited about David Fincher yeeeaay),Now, with all the discounts on ""men are from Mars and women are from Venus,"" I think that (according to Islam?) women having no souls sounds partially true. Why would someone latch oneself to another person, go to such novell-ish lengths to satisfy the emptiness that can never be filled? What is the point of Amy_amazing maneuvering? Poor Amy. She is so very lonely from the beginning to the end.The only somewhat believable character was Maureen, the dying mother, I liked her. An uncomplicated woman who found her happiness in her two creations, her twins, kicking abuser to the curb. ""That's the way to do it."" Oh, and another wisdom, communication is the key. It truly is.The book reminds me of Kreutzer Sonata with a happy (?) ending.
This was undoubtedly the most hyped book of 2012.  So I knew that sooner or later I would succumb to its lure. My one sentence reaction: It definitely deserves all the hype.The book starts out, appearing to me, like a fictionalized version of that real life California case.  You know the one with that guy named Peterson who killed his pregnant wife.  At least that is how it was playing out to me.  But Gillian Flynn had more surprises and twists to deal out in her novel.  Was it a bit over the top at times, you bet, but it was definitely a can't-put-it-down read.  It is scary to think that there are people in this world like Scot Peterson but Gillian Flynn gives us some ideas about how a psychopath operates as she lays out the story of the marriage of Nick and Amy Dunne.  I highly recommend this one to all mystery, suspense and thriller lovers.
This story, so innocent in the beginning, grabs you and doesn’t let you go. And every time you feel you know where the story is going, Flynn manages to spin the situation and totally confound you. There is one chapter told by Nick (the husband) and the next one by Amy (the missing wife). The timeline is non-linear, since Amy starts telling her side of the story 7 years before her disappearance and Nick starts the morning her wife goes missing. At some point, the two main characters’ timelines converge, which makes an interesting narrative technique. And after slowly building tension all along the book, I would have never expected this ending! Without giving any spoilers, when I just read the last line of the book, I was startled and sort of pissed at Gillian Flynn. But after sleeping on it, all I can say is that it is a brilliant way to end this story.
