Despite getting off to a bit of a slow, ponderous start, Flynn's ""Gone Girl"" really is a compelling read, all the way through to the very bitter end.  Beyond having a great twist on the modern day ""whodunit"" where Flynn really excels in this work is his examination of the further infantilization of modern American men, and an exposure of one of the secrets among men today regarding their views of women.  Sometimes recited only partially tongue in cheek, there is a widespread bit of common knowledge, or masculine folklore, that most men share among themselves: the belief that all women are crazy and the success of marriage is calibrating how much crazy one man can take.  True or not, the factual basis of that position is almost irrelevant when shared over such a broad spectrum. Flynn really captures that, in its extreme, in this work.
Whoo, LORD. Wow, what can I say about this novel?? One of the best fiction stories I've ever read. Sometimes I don't really like having to switch perspectives between characters when I read, but I am so glad this one did. From beginning to end, I'd say that this book was great. Lots of plot twists, which I love, and a completely unexpected ending. It is pretty long (for me), so I spread it out over a few weeks so I could read a chapter or two before bed. Perfect way to wind down, but not really, because IT STRESSED ME OUT!!! The most interesting thing I found about this book was how each character came with their own flaws. Which is good and bad, because then I found myself wishing I had someone to root for haha. I highly recommend this book.Extra: I tried to watch the movie and fell asleep really quickly.  I'll just stick to the book.
Amy and Nick Dunne were a lovely couple, their love one to rival the sappiest romantic pairing in the history of romances...that is until Amy disappears and Nick is the prime suspect in the disappearance. Things quickly escalate and ol' Nicky looks to be in a world of trouble. Though, this isn't the entire gist of the story. Oh no, it gets much stickier and leads you down roads that twist when you think they'll turn and zig when you think they'll zag. This novel is a thrilling mystery that had me scratching my head at its brilliance unfolded before my eyes. I was shocked at how things turned out about three-quarters through the book, and the ending is one I surely didn't see coming. Gone Girl is one of the best reads I've had this year so far, and I would recommend it to those who enjoy a...different view on unhappy marriages ""changing things up.
This book. THIS BOOK!Okay, first of all, it's a psychological thriller in ever sense of the word. It surprised me, it shocked me, it disturbed me..and it amazed me. I don't want to spoil anything, but Gone Girl was twisty and engaging and can't-put-it-down.I highly recommend it for lovers of thrillers, psychology, twisty surprise plots, very three-dimensional characters, and generally great writing.I also have to give serious slow claps to Julia Whelan and Kirby Heyborne, who narrated the audiobook brilliantly- with all the emotion, inflection, and tone needed to make characters come alive. They didn't fall into that common audiobook narrator pit where one's voice takes on a constant cadence that is annoying as all hell- they sounded like real people. It made for an even better, more chilling experience of the book.
