So being horribly behind the times I finally picked up Gone Girl. One of the twists had been moderately spoiled for me (SPOILERS AHEAD IN THIS REVIEW BTW) so I had a fair expectation of what was coming, however this book was still pretty surprising.At first I found the prose a little rambling, then as soon at the action began I found myself sucked right in. There may have been one or two moments between big events where I was like 'OK, I get it he's in a tricky spot shes hanging out,' but for the most part the story was completely engrossing and intriguing.That ending though. At some point the story takes an abrupt shift away from psychological crime thriller to 'We Need to Talk about Kevin' territory. A bold move from the author, and it surprises me that such a book is so popular (not a criticism, just surprised)
I hated almost all the characters in this book to some degree, but that's what I ended up liking about the book. What's kind of funny is that the characters were like no one else I've ever known, and usually I spend a book trying to figure out who characters remind me of.My only complaint, and this is not the author's fault, is that the price of the book is far too high. I bought it for my Kindle, but it took me several weeks to talk myself into it. A book review is not the place to go into a rant about the publishing industry's abuse of ebook prices, but it bugged me enough to actually hinder my opinion. Weird, huh?Anyway, I'm worried that giving any details at all about this book will ruin it for future readers, so you'll just have to trust me that it's fabulous and it's nothing at all like what you think it's going to be.
I had no idea what to expect with this story. I'd heard it recommended over & over so I bought it after scanning the blurb. The first half was gripping. Did he, didn't he? In the beginning, I didn't even know it was a question I should be asking. Then suddenly, I wasn't so sure. A book that makes me second guess myself is doing something right. Who was Nick, really? I think his sister, Go, put it best:“You’d literally lie, cheat, and steal—hell, kill—to convince people you are a good guy.”This sums Nick up in such a perfect way. I loved going into this book blind, so I won't give much else away. I'll just say if you like a good psychological mind game, or if you'd enjoy a thriller that's not really set up like a thriller—read Gone Girl. Here's hoping the movie is great too, but if not, at least we have the book.
This was a page turner for me.  I had never read one of Gillian Flynn's books before, but I really liked the style or her writing.  This book is unusual in that the story is told from the perspective of both characters (and not exactly in a linear fashion), but it was still easy to follow.  The descriptions of the characters in the book were so spot on that I could think of people in my own life that were basically mirror images.  The story was your typical ""love gone wrong"", however, the pages take you to places that the reader does not expect.  I must admit that I couldn't foresee the plot twists in this book and I love when that happens.  I read the book in a matter of days.  I stayed up much too late as I found that I didn't want to put it down.  I recently bought another book by the same author, but haven't started it yet.
When you keep in mind that the sociopathic motivations are intentionally used as an extreme example, they brilliantly illustrate the narcissism of modern courtship and marriage and provided plenty of conversation-fodder for my hubby of 12 years and I. They also kept the story entertaining. Kudos to Gillian Pike for all the nuances on the theme, and for the superb writing!But compared to the book, the movie's screenplay sucked. Not sure why the author of a novel would insist on also writing the adapted screenplay -- they're two entirely different media and some of the beautiful metaphors Gillian Flynn painted in the book were completely lost in the film. She should've handed the reigns over to an experience screenwriter. That being said -- Ben Affleck & Rosamund Pike were brilliantly cast and delivered great performances.
