Its one of those books where I borrowed it, read it and I just have to have it in my book collection. And Gillian Flynn is one of the authors on my list to read all of her books. ""Gone Girl"" is about a marriage gone totally wrong. Its about a boy meeting a ""really cool chick"", and this girl turns out to be not what he thought she was. This book had so many hooks in it I couldn't put it down! I kept thinking ""did he kill her?"" I was on her side in the beginning, then out of no where, in some weird twist, I was on HIS side. The ending is a bit of a downer, it left me hanging and curious what was going to happen next. is there going to be a part two? a sequel? or maybe that's just what the author was going for. She wanted us to finished the story. Make us wonder what happened. What do YOU think happened?? Read this book and find out!
This is a difficult book to review without giving anything away. It's about a marriage that has begun to fall apart when the wife goes missing. Did the husband do it?I thoroughly enjoyed reading this book. It's told in alternating narrative and both main characters are writers. It's so well-written with such intricate details and insight into relationships between men and women and real characters with inside jokes. Halfway through the book, I was already looking forward to rereading it, and by Part Two I had forced my boyfriend to start reading it. He got custody of the book when I fell asleep and stayed up until 2am to finish it.Gone Girl is clever, fun, edge of your seat reading. Tonight, we're going to see the movie and can't imagine how they'll translate it for the screen.-Katie O'Rourke, author of Monsoon Season
GONE GIRL did everything that an unbelievable novel is supposed to do. It angered, impressed and confused me while also making me want to devour the next page regardless of what I was missing in the real world. I took turns hating the leads then questioning and rereading whole passages searching for missing truths so that I could ""choose the right side"" and rejoice when the wronged party was eventually vindicated and victorious in the end.Hmmmm, nope.I HATED the ending and felt that I missed pages and was being forced to suspend belief beyond possibility, but after I thought about it  for a bit I realized that both characters stayed true to themselves till the end. Gillian Flynn took the care and time to craft these flawed, broken, selfish, HUMAN BEINGS and she knew how their crazy elaborate story would end.
