I'd been warned that this book was ""twisted"" by fellow readers, so of course I had to check it out to see what the fuss was all about. After getting about half way through the book ""twisted"" seemed like the best definition for what was happening on the pages I was turning; but after completing the book-it seems almost an inadequate word.It was a little slow for me to get into at first, as it was a different writing style than I was used to, but as soon as I got into it I was hooked and had to know what would happen next... Right up until the ending, which I hated-but I think you're supposed to. You hate it, but then you think ""that's so very human-and extremely messed up, which makes it even more human.""  I'd recommend reading it if you're into mystery, or love a good twisted tale.
I was hesitatant  to read this book since it was a new author to me and I read mysteries/suspense/ police procedurals quite regularly. They are many times poorly written. At first I was disappointed because each chapter switched from the perspective of the husband, then wife and alternating throughout the book. It proved however to be an excellent choice since the characters were emotionally complex and had been living separate lives internally. This is an enjoyable book and full of some surprises when the reader becomes one of the two characters privy to his/her own thoughts. It is enlightening and simultaneously frightening ! The actual plot is fast moving with plenty of other support characters to make you question reality, facts and devious fantasy. I would recommend reading it as it it put together quite well .
To be honest, when I first began reading this book, I was not all that impressed. Action took a while to set in, but when it did... boy! I sure spent my money right! This is another one of those stories where when you try to predict what will happen next it is never what you thought it was. The suspense and the mystery wrapped me in its cocoon and trapped me there. Gillian Flynn sure did quite the number in this!Like I said before, the only fault I could detect of this book is that the action was slow-coming. No matter though. A setting had to be developed somehow, right? :)I would recommend this to anyone that likes surprises, hanging onto every word, and sitting on the edge of your seat out of anxiousness to know what comes next. Hopefully, you will enjoy it like I did (and continue to do)!
Within the first few pages of Gone Girl I was smiling, settling in for a long read. It’s rare that you slip into a book and think, yes, this author is going to take me for a ride. The book is inventive, the structure of the story is unique, her approach to character development is great. You grow to love and hate (perhaps love is too strong – none of the characters are very loving) the characters, and then you hate and love them in reverse order. And Flynn accomplishes this with a deft hand.There’s been much said about the ending. I don’t think it’s the neat wrap up that I had wanted, but it’s an ending that’s true the story and to the characters Flynn has developed. While I can’t say that I liked the ending, I thought it was perfect for the book. Excellent read that I have recommended to many friends.
Read in November, 2014format Mass Market Paperback (edit)review Brilliant. Once I started reading, was very hard to put down. It wasn't difficult to follow the story and I especially liked the thought process, that the two principal characters went back and forth..a she said, he said type of dialog. As the story unfolds and the wife Amy goes missing, his attitude at the time kept bringing Scot Peterson to mind, the way he reacted in the spotlight when Lacy went missing. Of course one was fact and one was fiction and although some things in the story reminded me of the Peterson tragedy it is quite a different story and outcome. The subject matter is for the mature open minded readers so anyone with a puritan mindset and an aversion to profanity might not want to go here. (less)flagcomment ·
