You read some books on the bestseller list and you go, hunh? Not this one. Gone Girl deserves its place in the pantheon and will be on people's lists for years to come.The greatest strength of the book is neither its intricate plot nor the devious interplay between the characters; it's the language. This author has more than an ordinary gift. She can make the words jump right off the page and bite you with their truth, and with dark humor. Zingers can be found on every page. Reading Gone Girl felt like a weekend on some hallucinatory drug. It made me queasy at first, then just one long high that kept getting more and more intense.More than 5000 other reviews have been written before mine, so I won't bother to summarize the plot. If you read just one book this year, read Gone Girl.
I just felt the need to add some perspective to the  NYT review the includes the comment “Readers who prefer more virulent strains of unreality…”The plot is dramatic and taken to an extreme, but not by so much that it  strains credulity.  People like Amy Dunne  do exist, and this book nails the feeling of frustration of those who have been destroyed by them and are left to watch helplessly as they continue to con and charm an unsuspecting world. For anyone who has been involved with a psychopath this book hits close to home. For those who dislike the ending: Yes it’s not satisfying, but it is exactly the way these relationships usually wind up.Brilliant in its story telling and ratcheting up of tension, and disturbingly accurate in the portrayal of flawed and disordered people.  A must read
I absolutely loved this book!  Once I started, I hated to put it down when I had to do something else.  This is so well-written, and such an engrossing story.  It keeps you guessing for a while, then you can't wait to see how things turn out.The writing is witty and brilliant.  One of my favorite lines reminds me of the way my sister and I talk, trying to be funny.  Nick is talking about a conversation he had with a police officer, where Nick had used the word ""scrapping,"" and Nick says to himself, mocking the cop, ""Scrapping?  What is this scrapping you speak of?""  That just cracked me up.  Also, many of the pop culture references and movie quotes were a very nice touch.This is the first Gillian Flynn novel I have ever read, but it certainly won't be the last.
This is a real page-turner -- I read it over the course of 2 days and was fascinated by all its twists and turns.  Just when you think you know what's going on, something happens to make you see things differently... and again, and again.  The main characters are ""crazy"", but as ""every jest has some truth in it"", this tale can make you think about your own relationships and those of others you know.  Isn't there often some degree of pretense, of hiding some of who we are, no matter how close the relationship?  Can any husband or wife truly ""know"" each other?  People often argue violently, but don't usually cross the line into actual violence.  But there is sometimes a thin line between sanity and insanity.  These characters live on that line, and they take you on a wild ride.
Kept me up and on my toes  nothing predictable....would and have told others also ... now I can watch the movie
