This was my first Gillian Flynn novel and what a great read.  I loved the first person narrative with the husband and wife.  This type of writing is not done all that much and therefore I found it very interesting way of telling this two sided story. I will not go into the story-line, many other reviews have already done this so I will just rate the book on its elements (0 to 5 being highest):Protagonist Development: 5Antagonist Development: 5Minor Character Development: 5Storyline: 5Setting: 5Theme: 5Writing Style: 5Overall Rating: 5I do not give many books a Overall Rating of 5 so to me this is a must read!
I finished this book a few days ago and I had to wait a few days to be able to write a review.  I feel so many emotions when I think about this story and the ending.  There is so much thought written into this story between the two main characters, I love that each chapter is different points in time from their different points of view.  You can't figure at first what kind of guy Nick is current time when his wife goes missing, he seems unaffected.  Meanwhile Amy tells the story of how they met and fall in love.  Then as the book continues and Amy's timeline is current you learn so much.  I applaud Gillian Flynn this writing is amazing.  I still don't know how I feel about the ending, not that there needs to be another book just so much left unsaid.
This book is unlike any I've ever read. It is full of suspense and mystery. It is extremely difficult to explain how good the book is, because you just start reading it and become generated in the story. The basic premise is that a husband one day comes home to find his wife missing and obvious signs of struggle. However, that does no justice to what this book becomes. The investigation leaves you literally convinced of innocence and guilt every other page. Unlike many books, I never had that thought of knowing something for sure, ie: ""Well, there is absolutely no way that character was involved at all."" Literally I had no real clue until Gillian Flynn wanted me to have a clue. I would recommend this to anyone in the mood for a new kind of suspense.
I was looking forward to reading this book because so many people have loved it.  I was not disappointed for the most part!  The twists and turns in the books were great and ones that I didn't see coming.  My only hang up on this book was for the hype that it does have I didn't understand why the ending wasn't more.  It felt almost unfinished but in a way it sort of worked.  This is a quick read though as you are always wanting to know what will happen in the next chapter and if he did kill his wife!This is a great crime novel that I could see becoming a good movie at some point because of the hype it does rightfully have.  Even if you aren't into that crime who-done-it sort of novel it also has a thriller element that you might enjoy.
Holy moly cannoli!! What an awesome book!!! I read this book in 5 days, and loved every page of it! I've never read a book with so many twists, turns, truths, lies, mystery, suspense, secrets, psychotic minds in my life!!! This was my first book I've read by Gillian Flynn, and am excited to read her other books. I found myself gasping out loud with each secret that was revealed. I found my mouth hanging wide open as I read on. You really can't tell people about this book farther than what happens in the first 2 chapters, without giving something away. Bravo Gillian Flynn. The ending was so crazy, I didn't want it to end!! This would be a good book club book. AMAZING!!
Wow, wide range of opinion on this one. I for one loved it. I loved the alternating points of view, & trying to figure out who could be believed, & for what purposes.Obviously, many people object to the ending. I guess I can see why people have that opinion, I just happen not to share it. I found the last twist to be great, another act of manipulation worthy of Walter White.I will say that the one would-be suitor who conveniently shows up just a few hours away from where she ended up in MO was more than a little contrived. That part of it jumped the shark for me.But I actually thought the author reeled it back in nicely after that, & again, found the conclusion very satisfying.Can't wait to read more from Gillian Flynn.
A great book that will have you wishing there was more to the story of Nick and Amy Dunne. A must read.
I could not put this book down. It was the best book I have read in a long time. The suspense is great.
You need to read this. It grabs you by the heart! I loved it so much, now I would like to see the movie
This book is incredible! I read it in 12 hours straight. While it is an incredible thriller and keeps you hooked, the book is also a great commentary on relationships and marriage. I loved how the author interweaves the mystery in the plot with a very intimate look at the relationship between the two characters. The plot line unfolds in a way that makes you want to know more, and the nuanced writing about the characters and their lives gets you invested in their story. I won't say anymore to prevent spoilers.The book also highlights the media circus surrounding events of high-interest and has a pretty satirical and interesting take on that.I highly recommend this book! Read it before it is made into a movie and ruined!
This book was just way too much fun - and I mean that in a good way.  I'm taking a leisurely drive down the garden path of the story, when BAM - right in the middle it makes a u-turn and we are on the damn highway doing 90 miles an hour (commonly referred to as a plot twist).  Sweet Mother of Mercy!There is not much to say without the risk of giving up some detail that's best left secret.  Soooo many time I wanted to just take one little peek at the end to see what happens to Nick and Amy.  But I didn't.  I survived the heart pounding suspense and made it to the end of a very satisfying read.I must, must must check out more books by Ms. Flynn
Gone Girl is an incredibly well-written and original page-turner, one of the best I've read in a long time and one that haunts your thoughts long after you finish it. It begs to be read carefully since every word is used precisely and the descriptions articulate truths that will resonate with the reader. It is impossible to put down and each chapter ends with material that forces the pages to turn. I liked the ending and thought it fit the novel's themes and characters, but even if you don't, the experience of reading it is worth the price. Be warned: there is a fair amount of ""R rated"" material and language; it's not a novel for those who are offended by profanity.
All I can say is the stories and the characters are twisted, emotionally and mentally. I like how the author ""built"" her characters through out the book. When I was getting to the part where everything starts to come together and I kinda have an idea what might have happened, I paused to thought that, since the story and the characters were so twisted, the author must had a twisted mind herself to write such novel with such plot. She is truly a talented writer with a great imagination. I like the story, I like how itwas developed and the psychologically thinking behind all that took place in the story. It kept me wondering even after I've done with the book. I look forward to seeing the movie, I hope the movie is as good as the book!
This is my first Gillian Flynn novel - on to the next! Gone Girl is truly thought-provoking at a time when it seems most are just word count strung together more or less coherently. The alternating viewpoints of Nick and Amy, which engage the reader with each character, provide a ""real time"" perspective. The ending will cause shudders through the imagination.A side note which I feel is of particular importance: the editing for Gone Girl is excellent. I rarely provide reviews because there are only so many ways to say ""the book is probably good, but the editing was so poor as to cause massive confusion"". Not the case with Gone Girl. I can totally relate to Ms. Flynn's notations regarding the correct grammatical usage of ""me"" vs ""I"" by Amy.
VERY well written family saga.If this book does not grab you, hold your attention, give you chills then turns your sympathy upside down, then all I have to say is; you are either dead or an ET.( Even an AI would love it.) Flynn has men (no, not all men, thank God) pretty well pegged. Nick is able to learn, the hard way. Amy and he are something else together. Amy may be brilliant, but street dumb, Nick is neither.I switched my sympathy between them several times..  SPOILER OF A SORT,READ NEXT STATEMENT IF YOU WANT TO, BUT, I DID WARN YOU:  I an not real sure about a baby, as a solution, at the end, is a good choice. In the real world the dad would likely disappear.  It would be fun to see baby Amy Nick grow up. So a sequel maybe ?
Definitely deserving of it's status in the Best of 2012.  Gillian Flynn writes with razor-sharp insights into these deeply troubled, hateful but somehow lovable characters.  The mystery is intriguing, the plotting ingenious, the research excellent, but what I liked best of all was the examination of one of society's most revered institutions:  marriage.  As well, the social commentary and satire of America's media culture had me in stitches at times.  It seems the author allowed herself to have a great deal of fun with this novel.  I have already ordered her first two novels and hope to enjoy them.  Although she states that she didn't structure this book to allow for a sequel, I for one beg Gillian Flynn to revisit our deeply disturbed duo.
Gone Girl is dark and Gone Girl is gritty. Gone Girl is about the thing that goes bump in the night, but the monster is actually the person that you love the most and the person you thought you could always trust, but really they’re only out to get you. Gone Girl is about a modern American marriage, which here is synonymous with The Other American Horror Story.For spoilery reasons I feel like it’s almost impossible to discuss the plot without ruining at least part of the story. Amy Dunne is a young wife who goes from loving to resenting her husband with some vaguely good reasons. Nick Dunne is a young husband who goes from loving to resenting his wife with some vaguely half-assed reasons. It spirals out of control from there.
This is the best novel I have read in the last two years. As a psychotherapist, I can say that Ms. Flynn did a excellent job describing a narcissistic Nick and a very intelligent sociopath, Amy. It would be interesting to get women's views on the insights into American men described in Amy's diary. Perhaps some of it is true. High intelligence, creativity and a sociopath personality make Amy (and others like her) so highly dangerous. Poor Nick is no match for her and is completely trapped at the end of the novel. Some have expressed that they would like to see a sequel. Why? I would suspect that they don't want to see her get away with all of it. I can't wait until I see what they do with the novel in the movie coming out on October 5th.
Put one psycho-bitch wife (Amy) together with one narcissistic husband (Nick) and you get one heck of a detonation. Marriage values sure have come a long way...Gone Girl is a suspenseful crime thriller that is absolutely over-the-top intriguing. When the wife goes missing, of course the first suspect is always the husband! In every aspect, the cheating bastard is forever guilty. But wait, just when you have it all figured out, the story comes to its climax, and all hell breaks loose. (It reminds of the movie War of the Roses. Certainly, there is no correlation but the fact that husband and wife stay together with such vengeful dislike, they might as well off each other.) Brilliant story! Absolutely Fabulous! Highly Recommend!
A book that will keep you on the edge of your seat and wanting to see what could possibly happen next!
It was slow at first but started picking up half way through and surprised me in the best way possible
great ending to a book that started off a little slow but built into a great ending , very different .
Don't worry - no spoilers here.  AND don't listen to the negative reviews!  I thoroughly enjoyed this book: the writing style, the page-turning prose, the characterization, and the interesting, thought-provoking plot.  I could hardly put this book down, so it's a quick read.  The ending is surprising, but if you really stop to consider these characters and who they are, you'll realize that the book could not have ended any other way.  The ending is consistent with the characters.  Many of the themes in this book will make you THINK and will force you to evaluate some of the relationships in your life (past and present).  Bottom line? It's entertaining, thought-provoking, and definitely recommended...and I can hardly wait for the movie!
It is hard to put a good book down, but when it is an audio book you can take it with you.  I was grocery shopping while listening to the story. I could not stop. I think I bought extra groceries just to finish the book!This book is full of twists and turns.  It takes you into the mind of a brilliant, but obsessed woman.  She will do anything to have her way. I'm glad I did not marry her ! I expect this book has made me a better husband.  I certainly appreciate my wife even more...The ending is somewhat unexpected, but believable.The narrators did a great job of making the book come alive.I will find the other Flynn novels, and listen to them.  If they are half as good as this one, I will enjoy them thoroughly.
This novel is exquisitely crafted; even the title holds the onion layers of Flynn's prose.What seems so overt on the face of the first fifty pages - a missing wife, with the husband under increasing suspicion (and rightfully so, given the fact that their marriage is in trouble when she disappears, and he's not been the perfect husband), becomes a labyrinth of introspection and insight on the differences between how people are perceived and what they truly are.Many people have complained about the end of the novel, since it isn't tied up in a nice, neat bow - all questions answered, etc. Well, neither is life; people drift in and out of lives, you never know the entire story - I thought it was a perfect ending.
I wanted to read the book before seeing the film, but now I'm unsure if I want to see the film. As a divorced person who has seen how dangerous one-sided emotional control can be in a marriage, this story bright me back to many times my ex treated me such as to manipulate my behavior with his own toxic actions and words. I thought the characters were very well-developed and relatable, especially having been a married young adult. The psychology and social understanding behind the story really make you think about your own relationships and interactions with those around you. Excellent, somewhat intellectual study of relationships and how seriously they can be taken and they can take us. Highly recommended for young adults and older.
This book makes my short list of favorites. The book starts off with a light and witty tone that leads you to believe you are in for a humorous version of some Life Time drama....Shallow, but very enjoyable. Then suddenly you are in shock and caught so completely off guard that you can't do anything but turn the next page as fast as you can. The tone of the story changes and everything you read before turns into something so completely insane you just don't know what to believe anymore! Things continue to get darker and darker and the revelations more mind blowing. I finished this book and could only sit and shake my head with wide eyes and an unbelieving smirk on my face. Shock. This book is crazy, insane, unbelievable.... AMAZING.
The blurbs on the book jacket are all true. This is one of the smartest works of fiction I've ever read. [It lands somewhere between 'Chicklit' and 'Woman's fiction' in that it mocks both of them. It's more David Foster Wallace-ish.] It is funny, very funny, and sad, and mostly true. Gillian Flynn has pretty much figured out the man/woman marriage/happiness thingy. Add to that slick and witty commentary on American culture and the writer's paradox (how much `truth' to tell) and you've got ""Gone Girl."" But, fair warning: If you're happily married you might want to skip this one and just keep up the masquerade. (Note to Fylnn's husband: You've been warned.)
This is such an enjoyable and, at the same time disturbing story. Gillian Flynn is able to go into the dark thoughts and feelings way beyond the surface chaff usually depicted by writers about a marriage. She puts a light on the dark, morbid thoughts and feelings dredged up from primitive infantile aggression that I suspect most of us have but can hardly believe and try to ignore.  And she has created a character who not only has these thoughts, put spends months planning and acting them out. And the idea that it's these lizard-brain primitive feelings that not only exist, but that become the glue that binds this couple together and defines who they are.As a family therapist I find this story outrageous yet believable.
The author starts off slowly, and almost mundanely, with a narrator reading from her diary. Before you are even aware of it, you find yourself being drawn into a black hole of totally unexpected twists and turns, growing darker and more menacing throughout, until you realize it's a thriller you're reading, and you have no idea where it's going. You only know you must find out, and so you can't put the book down.Fabulous writing; author has total control of her subject matter and language (the intricate and complicated plot she contrived plot is dazzling).Only reservation is that I felt the ending was disappointing, didn't work for me at all. It just didn't follow, not logical. Still, totally worth reading.
The story of this book, with its twists and turns is spellbinding. But what I actually enjoyed most about it is the quality of the writing. Gillian Flynn has created a voice for each of her primary characters that is incredibly authentic. Her ability to capture the thoughts and mental outbursts of the character left me feeling completely engrossed in each of them. One tiny negative observation: Ms. Flynn is so clever with the voice of each character, that it sometimes borders on the too clever. These phrases sometimes took me out of the story and back in to my own role as a reader, rather than a voyeur watching something real unfold.AND, this is one the most well-written, most downright enjoyable books I have read in years!
