Gone Girl lays out the catastrophic devolution of a marriage doomed to fail and the evolution of a sociopath to a psychopath.I love it when a writer defines characters so well that you understand their bad decisions. You don't shake your head and think why on earth did he/she do/say that? You know the context. You know the characters intimately, and like it or not, it all makes sense in the fictional world presented to you. Doesn't mean you agree, but you understand. That type of context is incredibly difficult to convey in a 2-hour movie, but I will be seeing Gone Girl when it's released, knowing before I purchase my ticket that it can never be as good as the book. But at least I will have the context.
Gone Girl is a very interesting novel. I thoroughly enjoyed the book, though there was some harsh language that I feel the readers could have been spared. I loved the way the plot took a dramatic twist about a third of the way through. I was feeling like I could predict what was going to happen at first. All of a sudden the twist came out of no where and I was thrown hook, line and sinker into the crazy circumstances brought on by the antagonist. I would suggest this to people who like unpredictability and intrigue. However, the bad language was a bit over done. So if you don't want to read  the ""f  bomb"" you may think twice. I wish movies and books could  curb that word. We could all get along without it.
