I enjoyed this book so much - I was MIA until I finished it!  I was excited when I woke up in the middle of the night so that I could read a few chapters.  I wouldn't leave my house without my Kindle - so that I could read anytime I had a chance.  It was a wild ride with twists and turns that I never expected.  I am in awe (and a little frightened) by the authors' imagination - and would be a little worried if I were her husband!!  The intricate plots were so carefully concocted - so dark and devious, they were intoxicating.  It was good that I didn't fall in love with ANY of the characters, so that I could just go for the ride and not worry about who won out in the end.  I highly recommend this book!
Wonderful in every sense. Let me explain. The story telling is flat out brilliant. The characters are real, in  which you can identify.  Some characters in this book have you thinking, I've met someone like this before.  I have dated a real-life sociopath. My only saving grace was, he was not a planner like Amy. Almost the opposite, instant gratification. Didn't like waiting. I believe the ending of this book is fitting.  It couldn't have been something neat and tidy. The ending,  just is...... Ask yourself something,  Isn't this ending just like life? It just is, then you move on in a different direction, trying to reinvent yourself, knowing you are still that same person all that stuff happened to.
Whether you love or hate Nancy Grace and all the other shows that delve into missing people and murders then you'll love this book!Gilliam Flynn expertly writes in three different voices.  One view from the diary of the missing wife, Amy, another view in Amy's ""live"" voice, and the view of the husband.Throughout the novel these points of view are woven into a believable story of what happens when boy meets girl and they play the mating game.  What happens when the marriage falls apart and if anyone can survive it.Love this book!  I couldn't put and down and didn't want it to end.  It is one of those rare books that will stick with you long after you've finished it.
A nearly flawlessly plotted novel, and a haunting, dark meditation on happiness, adulthood, love and marriage. Do we ever really know loved one? Is that even important to a ""successful"" marriage? Do we even know ourselves? Or are we just a long series of a charades set against a moving backdrop of TV-inspired cliches that we always try to emulate? The questions don't stop there, and they are unsettling and urgent as they are asked through the gripping plot developments of this psychological thriller. Is love a gift or a curse? Is it a verb or a noun? Are we better people if we think we'll be killed for being less than our best?Damn, this is one of the best books I've ever read.
My mind is seriously reeling right now! I have been twisted forward, and back now I am not sure which way is up! If the upcoming movie is half as good and twisted as this book then hoorah!A wife goes missing, the husband doesn't have an alibi and he has a huge secret, a crime scene that looks suspcious and a whole situation that stinks! You automatically assume that the husband is guilty. Remember what happens when we assume!Amy Elliott Dunne is smart, too smart! Nick Dunne is the smart, stupid man ripe for the picking.This is a topsy, turvy tale that will leave you wondering if you really know the person you are married to. Question everything, believe nothing!
This is one of those books that leaves you thinking.  How the author brilliantly unveils the truth behind a husbands and wife's less than perfect relationship.  It is not predictable by any means.  As I was reading the book I continually envisioned certain outcomes all of which turned out to be false.  The research and depth into a troubled, yet brilliant persons mind must have been deeply study and investigated while writing the book.  It starts off slow but half way through I couldn't put the book down.  I do not read books too often, but if I had to recommend one that would be worth investigating the time while keeping up with a busy day to day schedule this would be the one to lose sleep over.
I was hesitant to read it, given all the mixed reviews, but I am glad I did.....this is not your typical happy ending story....I sure hope there is a sequal coming....Amy is one twisted character and Nick could be any of us just caught up in a web of a ""pshyco bi***"" It was very well written and just when you thought this is what might happen next, you are totally taken the other way around! In the first part of the book, I did have the feeling that Amy was not all that she was telling us! Come on - I am a very easy going person, but the stuff she says she let her husband slide with, does not happen in a real marriage! This is not a ""brainless"" book nor an easy read but it is a must read for sure!
Want a real page turner for the beach? Gone Girl by Gillian Flynn is the book for youGone Girl is Narrated by Nick Dunne and his wife, Amy, in alternate chapters. The story begins when Nick and Amy lose their jobs and move from New York City to Nick's hometown of North Carthage, Mo. and into a McMansion. No one is happy--especially Amy. When Amy disappears, Nick is the obvious suspect.In the beginning Amy seems almost perfect but then cracks begin to appear same with Nick.If you're reading a book you can't put down, Kindles are great you can tuck them in your purse and be on your way.
I know I'm the last person on the planet to read this book, but sometimes it takes the release of the movie to get my butt in gear because I refuse to see the film without first reading the book.  It's my personal philosophy and I'm sticking to it.  Anyway, the book.  It was amazing.  Any author who can make me simultaneously love and hate two characters is a master at her craft.  I love Nick and Amy, I hated Nick and Amy, I wanted to kill Nick and Amy.  Flynn's writing style is totally approachable and unassuming which I love.  My only critique... the ending.  I know WHY Flynn did what she did, but that doesn't mean I need to like it.  Still 5 stars because it was without a doubt a great book...
This story caught me up and took my imagination on a long and twisting road.  There is nothing that is what it seems to be, and about halfway through the book I started wondering about my own powers of perception.  The characters are compelling, and deeply complex.  The author's writing style is almost conversational, and written from the viewpoints of the main protagonists.  These two are locked in a passive-aggressive battle, and I kept turning the pages as their stories peel back the individual layers of history.  It was very hard to put down, and lingers after turning the last page.  I would like a follow-up book, because real closure is not provided.  Does one ever really know their spouse?
