This seems to be a really polarizing book! Most times when I read, I want my heroes and heroines to be people I'd want as friends. You don't get that in this book. But what you get is a talented writer who gives you details that put you into the place where the story takes place and into the heads of the people in the story. There are some weak points with plot, like the female protaganist opening up to strangers when there was no valid reason for her to do so. And -- mild spoiler -- the end isn't so convincing, to me at least, because it seemed to me the hero gave in too easily. But these flaws can be overlooked because no book can be perfect. The writing is where this book has its strength.
I had already watched the movie, which I enjoyed except I was very frustrated by the ending. I guess, without including spoilers, I wanted to see if the book was more convincing about why the husband would end up where he was by the end of the story.  I loved the writing of the novel, it was detailed, fast paced, descriptive and intriguing and once I started I really didn't want to stop.  I still don't like how it ends, and maybe I just wish there were a sequel so there could be hope that this wasn't the end. Anyway, if you like characters who are screwed up and complex, gritty, real and yet unlike the people in your life, you hope, this is a compelling, entertaining and well written mystery.
I love this book - it has excellent characterization (even the minor roles), which really adds to the story without feeling inundated with pointless fun-facts.  I saw the movie first, and hadn't heard of the book until then, but it does a better job of building the story (as books typically do).  Gillian Flynn does an amazing job of painting a picture that keeps you guessing, lacing the story with witty humor and relatable current societal references, and of course the dramatic plot.  I'm not typically one for a ""mystery novel,"" but this book is truly a favorite.  I read the whole thing on vacation of my kindle, absolutely could not put the thing down even while tanning on the beach.
Some of the best fiction I've read in a while.  Started it on the weekend and, well.... there went the entire weekend because I couldn't put it down.  Well paced, well written story of a marriage gone from heaven to hell in a few short years.  It's pretty dark so may not be for everyone, but I thoroughly enjoyed it.  A look into the mind of a scary but brilliant sociopath.  I suspect there may be more than a few women out there who will read this book and secretly fantasize ""wish I'd thought of that.""  The difference between a sociopath and the rest of us - we only think about it.  I would love to see Ms. Flynn write a sequel to this because there's a lot of story line left to tell.
Gone Girl starts out as a mystery...seemingly perfect couple, married 5 years, beautiful wife disappears.  It's a wild ride from there, and it really keeps you guessing.  It ends up becoming a character study of truly psychotic behavior.The book makes you think about how much importance society places on appearances and how significant public opinion can be.I understand the negative reviews...some people need a hero that they can root for and that is almost impossible to do with these characters.BUT...the writing was exceptional.  It was though provoking and highly entertaining.  Completely warped - in a good way!  I have never read anything quite like this.  FANTASTIC!!!
