Gone Girl"" is a masterfully crafted novel by an extremely talented writer  I found myself at times holding my breath and not wanting to put the book down.However, I am not terribly sure that I'm glad I read it!This book is not for the faint hearted.  It is a dark, twisting walk through the corridors of a very bad marriage and it is impossible to finish it without being affected.The psychological aspects of this story reach out and pull you in and make you wonder if it is possible to ever truly know anyone.  READER BEWARE!!!
Gone Girl is one of the best crime/mystery novels I've ever read.  My office book club chose it for our April selection and had a marvelous time discussing it.  The style it is written in, with the alternating points of view, is so unique.  Everyone in my book club had a hard time keeping our lips zipped until everyone had finished it - you really can't say anything about it for fear of spoiling the surprises for other readers!  Can't wait for the movie; however, I've heard that the ending has been changed for some reason.  I hope not, as the book's ending was completely consistent with the character development.  All I can say is, if you haven't read Gone Girl, you need to!  Loved it.
There are two writers that, in the words of Stephen King, are unsurpassed in their ability to ambush the reader; to lay suspense-ridden traps for you.  They are Ira Levin (Rosemary's Baby) and Cornell Woolrich (The Bride Wore Black).  To these must be added Gillian Flynn.  ""Gone Girl"" has some genuinely stunning surprises embedded in a terrifying story of betrayal and manipulation.  It's a lot like Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf? meets Presumed Innocent.  I finished it in one long night of reading.  It's just that un-putdownable.
This is one of the most engaging books I've read in years! Reminiscent of Patricia Highsmith's Ripley series, Flynn keeps you engrossed from start to finish. Being that person who virtually always figures out the denouement  of books and movies before their end, I appreciated being kept guessing throughout  the book. I savored this story for a couple of weeks of evenings, though all I really wanted was to read from start to finish, in one long sitting.While some say the book's conclusion was disappointing, how else could a novel about complicated human relationships have ended but ambiguously, thus a lot like real life. I hope Flynn writes a sequel to this very satisfying read!
Gillian Flynn is a true mastermind!  Gone Girl kept me guessing with every chapter...who killed Amy? Is she even dead? And then later, came the acts of a truly psycho wife.I enjoyed seeing this story from both sides. Both characters were well developed. Even after finishing the book,  I still cannot decide if Nick is a victim of a very angry and vindictive wife OR does he deserve all that came his way?  All the while,  seeing Amy's perspective helped understand the thoughts and the ""why's"" behind her twisted mind.Highly recommended for those who seem to figure out the plot line early in the game. This book will keep you  guessing until the last page!
It is ""Amazing"" how Gillian Flynn can write with great accuracy the two-sided aspect of a person's psyche.  We all have them...the darker side and the public-normal side.  The character Amy Elliotte Dunne, artfully created by Ms. Flynn, depicts the brilliant, beautiful, sympathetic persona of a psycho bitch; seamlessly displaying this two-dimensional personality. Nick Dunne, an absolute cad of a husband, eventually becomes the sympathetic, misunderstood victim readers want to see be avenged for what was done to him. This kind of character development requires skill and commitment to details.  Gillian Flynn has honed these skills, creating another great read to get lost in.  WHEW!!!
