I devoured this book, and since reading it, I consider myself a big Gillian Flynn fan.Flynn's writing style is superb, the structure of Gone Girl is unique, and the plot is riveting. The story and its ending are terrifying, especially because the characters and their lives appear so normal and mundane initially.Without spoiling anything, I'd say the characters are psychologically fascinating and Flynn offers a unique portrait of a sociopath via unreliable narration.Highly recommend for readers who love a thrilling mystery. Not recommended for those who only prefer a happy love story. And no, the ending is not a happy one either. Disturbing? Yes.
I loved this book.  There are surprises in this book that are just great. The surprise in the middle of the book, was not expected at all. The one thing I loved about this book is the ending.  I was waiting for the author to end the book one way, and when she ended how she did, it blew my mind.  I just loved it, and most authors would not have the courage to end it how she did.Please note, that Gillian Flynn does not have likable characters in her novels.  If you are a reader who likes the main character to be noble, wise, funny, and compassionate, I recommend that you do not read her novels.  If you want realistic and flawed characters, then she is the author for you.
Most engaging and suspenseful novel I can remember reading. I liked Nick and was sorry his wife was taken? Left him? I got to know Amy through her diary -- odd, over eager good wife. And then the story lifted off. Was I confused by an unreliable narrator or manipulated by evil people? I let the book take me on a terrifying, grief stricken, outrage inducing ride. I wish I could read it again.  Many threads fraying and not one left unwoven at the end. If I knew Ms. Flynn personally, I wouldn't turn my back on her. Her attention to detail reaches the point of obsession and held me enthralled even as I was trying to trip her up.  Masterfully done, Sharp Objects or Dark Places anyone?
One of the few thrillers that lives up to the hype. I did not want it to end.The characters are all very richly drawn, fully dimensional and your sympathies swing somewhat wildly between the two leads, Nick and Amy. Until you get into the cold heart of the story and everything is turned upside down! Darkly funny indictment of the current style of ""trial by media and popular opinion"". Skin-crawling creepiness from all directions.In all fairness, I'd seen the movie version of this tale prior to buying the book, so some of the key surprises did not surprise me-- and yet, I could not put the book down. Gillian Flynn's engaging writing style was an absolute treat.
