I'll start by saying the content and style of Gone Girl are not my typical cuppa tea—I'm not a mystery reader. I'm not a thriller-kinda person. To be honest, peer pressure made me read this book (not really, but all of my friends were, and it came highly recommended, so I caved). I can honestly say that Gone Girl is one of the best fiction books I've read in a long while — it sticks with you. It calls to you from you bedside table. It makes you turn off the tv to flip page after page. It tells you to leave work early to finish each chapter.Part One is amazing. Part Two is better. Part Three you never saw coming.Read this book. You won't be disappointed.
This is a wonderful, inventive story about the heady beginning of a relationship and the progressive decline of the ensuing marriage. Nick and Amy are complicated and often twisted characters who are well-suited to Flynn's descriptive writing. The plot turns are gripping, and although the characters are not always likeable, they are always compelling and entirely unique. I loved the sheer creativity of the story, and though the ending is not neatly wrapped up, I wasn't disappointed and couldn't picture the book having a different ending. The cast of supporting characters, especially Nick's sister Go, are equally interesting. Flynn is a wonderful writer in a league of her own.
Loved this quite scary story of a seriously deranged marriage ..... Excellent twists and turns to the (maybe) murder mystery from the two points of view.Many people disliked the ending, but I thought it was perfect for the book's characters.  If you insist on having some comeuppance for the bad person, don't read this - you won't like it.Kind of Spoiler, that you just won't get without reading it all - Nick becomes a dancing monkey.  While I hate that for him, its the just way it happened to end up for this fictional couple.My only dislike at all - the character Margo is called Go - strange and kind of annoying - I wish she had been named Sue or Mary.
A real roller coaster read! This is one of those ""I gotta get up at 2am and read some more"" books. My 2am reads end up lasting until 4am. I must admit, between 2am and 4am, some of the intricate details in this book get lost in my foggy early-morning brain. You just can't put this book down. You blame Nick....then you blame Amy. I now plan to read this book again - during daylight hours in order to digest the details. Begin the book and you are immediately consumed - you are there, watching the ""movie"" in the recesses of your brain ...  and, occasionally looking over your shoulder to be sure you are alone.  I will read this again, then, I will view the movie.
Wow! You should read this! Rarely if ever am I surprised at the plot and its progression in contemporary literature. I never wanted the book to end. The relationship of highly calculating individuals, hopes, and misfortunes - miscalculations - everything planned out by the writer so perfectly, you will think it all took place at some point with people she knew. You might also read your own thoughts, stolen or borrowed from a collective mind, that were not ever said out loud. You will catch yourself sympathizing with the wrong person, only to realize there were never a right one in the plot to begin with. Looking forward to her next book. Though doubt anything will beat this.
