'Gone Girl' is an extremely well written novel about a wife who has suddenly disappeared.  It soon becomes clear all is not what they appear to be; both the husband and wife are not nice people.  The author does a stellar job on keeping the reader guessing as to what exactly is going on.  The structure of the book, the prose, and characterizations are uniformly excellent.  My only quibble, which seems to be shared by many reviewers, is that the ending is somewhat disappointing.  But this is only a minor detraction from what is otherwise an enjoyable reading experience.Bottom line: a very unusual story of a marriage made in hell, handled well by a gifted author.
This book gives new meaning to ""can't put it down.""  With characters you love to hate, the plot twists and turns are amazing.  Yes, the central characters--one in particular--are sick people (both protagonists and antagonists in one) and no, you won't relate to them (if you do, perhaps you should be committed), but everything still feels, well, real, somehow.  The ending has gotten some negatives from readers, but I liked it.  The breathtaking finale was masterfully conceived and written, and not the cliche TV movie ending that some readers might prefer.  Go read it and know you are in the hands of an author who knows how to tell a story and creep you out at the same time.
I enjoyed this book with its psychological twists and turns. Fun characters that were easy to get to know. I lost sleep until I finished it. I might have liked a different ending but I am not sure what it would be. Two things about the book drove me nuts:1. Amy purchased a car for cash so no one could trace her.  In whose name were the plates? Did she just not transfer the title?2. I am not sure that an invetro clinic would impregnate Amy without the consent of her husband and a lot of paperwork and time. Did she pick up the fertilized eggs when the clinic was ready to destroy them? Did she keep them frozen at home and impegnate herself with a turkey baster?
When I first read the book description, I passed it over. No thanks, not my thing. But with the movie being released, the book was once again brought to my attention and I downloaded it to my Kindle. You guys ... OMG. I really did not think I would care for this book - I was oh so wrong. I am antsy and fidgety and on the edge of my seat waiting to see what's going to happen next. Gillian Flynn has woven an intricate and intriguing plot line that makes me want to stay up all night and finish it - while at the same time willing myself to put it away so it won't be over too soon. This is one of few books that I would rate well above five stars if the option were available!
Fiendishly clever and constantly surprising, this novel is the blackest comedy about marriage imaginable (actually it's unimaginable).  As it winds toward its close, the satire becomes more and more obvious and acid-tinged, and while the comedy certainly makes you cringe rather than laugh, anyone who doesn't catch a distorted disconcerting carnival funhouse glimpse of him or herself and spouse is fooling themselves. GONE GIRL breaks every contract that usually exists between author and reader and does so with panache; it's as manipulative as either of its main characters, and the reading experience may just help explain what it is that Nick and Amy see in one another.
Gone Girl"" is nothing short of amazing!  I loved this intriguing, fast-paced tale that lives up to its rave reviews. A love story, horror story and life story rolled into one huge tragedy.  Amy is beautiful, cunning and beyond manipulative.  Loved and worshipped by her doting parents, Amy lets nothing stand in the way of her perfectionism until she meets Nick, an All-American boy from Missouri.  Life with Nick demotes Amy to a status that is too ordinary, too mundane for this writer whose entire life has been revealed to the world in a timely and disciplined manner.  ""Gone Girl"" may be Amy's most amazing story, or is it?  Only Amy and time will tell.
This was the best book I have read in a long time! It had more twists and turns than I ever expected and this is what I loved! It had more than one jaw dropping twists and turns! This book will keep you enthralled from beginning to end! I listened to this book on tape and each day I could not wait to begin my long commute to and from work just so I could continue listening to this riveting story! Gillian Flynn is an eloquent writer. I will definitely read more of Gillian Flynn's books! If you saw the movie, please do yourself a huge favor and read the book! It was so much better than the movie and people (not me) say the movie was great! Nothing compares to the book!
I loved this book, and I even loved the ending which many seem to criticize. It is fascinating to me when an author can tell a good story and weave so many other elements into the book.  It is so rich especially if viewed through multiple lenses.  The way the book is written you are tossed around mentally and psychologically so that you almost feel psychotic yourself.  The end was clever, completely fulfilling well maybe not, but I don't think the author intended it that way.  The reader feels the same uneasiness and angst as the characters.  Did you really want an Amazing Amy ending...and if so does that make you any better then Amy's parents?  Just a thought....
While you may have heard this book is a thriller, a mystery, soon-to-be a major motion picture, and all your friends are reading this, what you may not have heard (and what your friends haven't said since they're nose-deep and turning the pages very fast) is that this is a beautifully written book. The character descriptions are enthralling. The voice of each is distinctive. You are drawn in, not just by the plot, but by the artful writing. Usually with page-turners I just want to find out what happens in a oh-please-hurry-up-and-tell-me-thank-goodness-that's-over-with style of reading.  I was truly sorry for this book to end and thought about it many days after.
I know a lot of people didn't like the ending, but I thought it was perfect and thought provoking.I like a book that still has me thinking about it a week, two weeks, a month later.And when I read my next novel which seemed impossible, and 3/4 of the way through, I thought I hate all the main characters and I would be happy if the book ended with me hating all the main characters, so long as they stay true to form. The book ended reasonably happily - but I think it would have been better if it didn't.I'm happy the next book I read ended in the normal satisfactory way, but I will forget it tomorrow. But I won't forget Gone Girl.
For the first few chapters one has the impression of a naive, spoiled girl of a woman.  Then one meets the strong, affable, loyal husband.  But, these things change drastically.  Stick with this novel.  It's beginning is a tease and might give you the impression of shallowness.  Hang in there.  By the end you have been treated to plot twists that you would not have predicted and writing that is very tightly crafted.  Your feeling about the characters will change drastically. You will come to see those first impressions as shadows projected onto a dark wall.  Like all horror stories, this one is deeply disturbing and it accomplishes that with a minimum of gore.
This book was so much more than your basic thriller.  There is enough action in the plot to keep you more than interested, but the characterization is also phenomenal.  It's not a serious read, but it's more than your basic fluff novel.  I don't want to give too much away, but basically, the book keeps you evaluating both the husband and wife who narrate the novel.  You can never quite be sure if they're being honest or what they're keeping from you.  Only from seeing both sides of the story can you get a full understanding of the plot and characters.  I highly recommend this book!
I really enjoyed this novel, although I'm sure I would have liked it even more, had I not seen the movie.  The development of the main characters throughout the novel was strong, as more was gradually revealed about each, often upsetting your notions and judgments about them. The presentation of Amy through her diary, and the back and forth with Nick's thoughts and feelings helps give what you think is an accurate perspective. The secondary characters, who are not always static, add to the conflicts Nick and Amy must face.  The story will keep you intrigued till the very end.  If you've seen the movie, but haven't read the book, you're still in for a treat.
I'm a book snob.  I generally like 3 genres -- depressing, funny or some sort of social criticism.  I get nervous if a book becomes mainstream, especially if it's likely to be sold at the nearest Wal-Mart.Gone Girl is the new ""hit"" book, debuting at book clubs around the US.  Its accolades include the NYTimes bestseller list & upcoming cinematization starring Reese Witherspoon.  I finished the book in two days.  It's clever & griping, ping-ponging the reader between two fully-developed narrators.  I have mixed thoughts on the ending, but thoroughly enjoyed the journey.100% recommend spending a weekend with this book[...]
Excellent craftsman, storyteller, magician with words. Amy and Nick's story is truly horrifying. Their story takes Thoreau's famous quote (""Most men lead lives . . .) and trivializes the sentiment to the point of being merely ridiculous.Has anyone been more desperate than Amy and Nick?It is a good read. A magnificent creation. And horrifying (I keep coming back to this descriptive) beyond apt appreciation. That two people now exist, even in creation, is frightening beyond comfort. THIS is what writing ought to do, take us to another place, another opening in the filament we never knew existed, and leave us after dropping us in.
This was my first Gillian Flynn novel, but now that I've read it I can't wait to read her other books. The story and characters are so intricately dark and mysterious, the plot so compelling, that I couldn't stop thinking about it when I wasn't reading.Some people dislike the ending, but without giving anything away, I think it fits perfectly with the characters that she has already set up, and I really can't see it ending any other way.If you're on the fence, but interested in the Fincher adaptation coming out in October, do yourself a favor and pick the book up. There's good reason Gillian Flynn has been compared to Stephen King.
This is not my usual type of book.  I got it as an audio book because I kept seeing it on all of the bestseller lists, and a friend recommended it because she really enjoyed it.  I have to say - it is not at all what I expected.  I kept listening and could not stop.  It is really surprising how the book unfolds, and I did not see the twists coming.  I just bought the two earlier Gillian Flynn books because I was so entertained by this one.  It is not for everyone - there are graphic violence and sexual content that may be inappropriate for some audiences.  Overall, I found it difficult to put down, and that is the highest compliment I can give for a book.
Keeps you on your toes!! The first part was rather slow but keep reading....it's worth it.
Great book. It was hard to put it down. I will definitely read other books by this author.
At first I wasn't too excited to read this book, when it became a best-seller. I had just tried to read the previous best-seller, 50 Shades of Grey, and wasn't at all impressed by it - such a bad writing. So I passed on this one for a while, thinking it shouldn't be a big deal either, despite being a thriller. And, to be honest, I don't really like to read thrillers. But this one is amazing. The way the author constructs the narrative and the way she always ends a chapter making you linger on to read the next one. One tip: Don't read it in bed if you have insomnia. You'll probably want to finish it that same night (I did that and finished it in 3 days).
I got this book a few months ago when it was $5 but I didn't end up start reading it until last week. But once I started, I was hooked! I started this book hating Nick, and comparing him to Scott Peterson when I would talk about the book. But at the second half of the book, I loathed Amy. I could not put the book down though!I don't get how people can say they hated the ending though. I loved it and even find myself thinking of how Nick and Amy would be NOW. If they would be divorced or still miserable together, if Amy would sabotage her son's friends or anyone else. I like that it didn't end on a happy or somber note, but on a cliffhanger.
Gillian Flynn has written a novel of marital dissolution in a novel way by presenting both sides of the story in alternating segments.  What you don't know is that one of the accounts is a fiction created to further implicate the other.  The ""mystery"" revolves around the disappearance of the wife, and there are so many twists and turns you may think you are in a labyrinth of classic complexity.  Gillian Flynn writes with a charged brilliance, electrifying the story with sharp dialogue and clearly defined characters.  When you come to the end of this roller coaster ride you may find yourself unable to think straight while you ponder what you just read.
The plot twists were amazing and unpredictable. I kept guessing who was telling the truth. The effects of parents on their children was a big theme as well as the change between a perceived relationship and a real one. In the beginning section of the book, I thought it was a novel exploring the changes a relationship goes, from ideal to realistic and the two characters showed the wrong way to adjust to the real person. The way it ends, I think absolves the failures to make a marriage work. I hope wording it that way doesn't give away the ending. The author did great writing in the voices of the different characters at different times of their story.
Gillian Flynn's third novel, Gone Girl, is an exquisitely twisted dissection of marriage, love, the malleability of identity, and the scourge of the media as it seeks to fuel a 24-hour news cycle. Flynn's structure and pacing are nothing short of genius as she parcels out the bits and pieces of the lives of her husband and wife protagonists through alternating first person chapters. Her prose is beyond perfection and magnificently displays the characters' personalities, pulling the reader into their relationship with all its ups and downs. There are turns in this novel that, to reveal here, would be absolutely criminal. Bottom line: Read This Book.
This book is fantastic. The writing is what drew me in at first - as I knew the story was going to be interesting at least. The characters are relatable and even though they are pushed to extremes there are still passages that everyone can associate with. I would highly reccomend this book. The only downside is that it went by too fast - even though it is a moderately lengthy 400 pages and it is really hard to find something to read after it as nothing seems to measure up.Overall very fast paced book that actually continues to surprise you to the very end.
