Having recently finished reading Gone Girl, I think it is worth pointing out that those who are unhappy with the ending consistently cite their desire for punishment of the guilty party(ies). The ending was good, it just didn't fit with the Western style ""good triumphs, evil is punished"" ending that Judeo-Christian audiences demand and are given in countless books, television shows, and movies in the US. Like a good Law and Order episode, you have to accept the fact that sometimes there are no perfect solutions to a problem, and at times evil may indeed be victorious. If you can accept that, then you'll enjoy the book (and the ending).
