Keeps you reading.Is every smart woman really just a sociopath? Is it true behind every smart man is just a smarter woman? Are all guys just big dicks but of course must have one to be the hero/villain? Am I a bad person if I notice how typecast everyone is but feel sorry for the person being the most manipulative while simultaneously constantly trying to break out of the literal literary mold that was created for her from birth?No spoilers because this is a well written book that I think most people who enjoy thriller mysteries will enjoy. And gives all new meaning to the phrase ""psycho bitch"".
I thought Gone Girl started out a bit slow, but hold on because it really blows up.  It is told from such a unique perspective that I can't say I've experience in another book.  It alternates between the male and female main characters.  They are narrating from their perspective, but never fully revealing the truth to the reader.  What results is that you are constantly changing your opinion about the characters and what actually happened.  Gillian Flynn creates the some of the most complicated, flawed and disturbing characters of any author writing today, and this book is no exception.  Highly recommended!
What with 7,000+ reviews already written, there's not much I can add, other than I want to vote ""5 stars.""  Getting through the first segment was like that first long ride up the hill on the roller coaster just waiting for the bottom to fall out.  Then I took the first plunge, where I thought ""A"" was true.  But no, I continued on, and found out it's ""B"" that is true.  But wait, no, it's really ""C""!!  My only disappointment was that I wasn't breathless at the end.  Yes, the whole thing was quite implausible, but sometimes it's fun to get drawn into a story like that.  I guess that's why they call it fiction.
Read this book after seeing it on several Best of 2012 lists, and after a recommendation by a close friend. Aimlessly skimmed the first few paragraphs and was immediately hooked. If you find yourself watching ""Dateline"" on Friday nights with a bowl of chocolate ice cream then this book is definitely for you. I for one had no issue with the ending. In fact, whenever I hear someone gripe about how ""awful"" it is, I can't help but wonder exactly what kind of ending they expected, having come to know the two main characters throughout the book. I will definitely be checking out the rest of Gillian Flynn's books!
A suspenseful story, with many twists, but with the idea of love and self identity playing in the mix. The ending leaves the reader to question whether to accept the couple or simply become bewildered by their relationship. However, with the characters describing their sentiments to the audience, it leaves the readers to root for the two main characters individually despite the horrid mistakes that they made to each other. Thus, resulting the audience to listen to both sides of the story. All in all, the novel introduces a fact that marriage is not always a blessing or a fairytale, but a trap to the other.
