I don't read a lot of fiction.  I noticed this book on the bestseller list and I saw it reviewed in a few magazines, it sounded interesting, but most fiction disappoints me.  One day I decided to buy it, I needed something to read.  IT WAS SO GOOD!  I enjoy Gillian's writing style, she actually had me caring about the characters, I wasn't skipping ahead or skimming paragraphs.  I was intrigued about what I was reading.  I love how her storytelling includes a brightness and a darkness within it.  I appreciate the authenticity and transparency in her characters.  I believed them.
I bought this for my son to read over vacation., & he couldn't put it down. Raved about it, although he rarely reads fiction.  Then it was my turn to read it & I loved it, too. I've also given the book as a gift to 2 friends.There are plenty of reasons why Gillian Flynn's novel has been on the best seller list since it's publication. Her writing takes you on a wild unpredictable roller coaster ride. The film, with which Flynn was involved, comes out Oct. 3rd. If you haven't yet read the book,  don't watch the movie trailer!Gone Girl is a terrific read.
This is a brilliantly written crime, psycho-suspense thriller. The story is told in a most imaginative and unique fashion. And it is a dark look into the heart of a very, very intelligent sociopath determined to always get their own needs fulfilled despite the harm this causes others. If you are new to it, don't see the movie first. Read the book. You're then free to see how they adapted this uniquely written work to the big screen. I won't say any more, lest I let a spoiler slip.This review originally published on https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1071927977
In one of her earliest novels, Agatha Christie cleverly tricked her readers by having the murderer doing the first person narration - and therefore averting suspicion with his lies.  This is not intended as a spoiler, but a parallel technique, but in a very different way, is used by Gillian Flynn...and her narrative weaves tricks that come thick and fast.  As a writer myself, I so enjoyed Gillian Flynn's skills in turning a simple 'missing person' story into such a fascinating read.  I was totally absorbed and I give it full marks.  And yes, the butler did it!  Just kidding!
I'm not a good writer myself, so I'm not able to produce a review that would do this book justice.  Just do yourself a favor and read it.  Set aside some blocks of uninterrupted time though; you truly will NOT want to put this book down.I listened to the audiobook version of this book via Audible.com.  The two narrators were wonderful, and the production quality was excellent.  Don't be afraid that the narrator(s) will ruin the book; if you enjoy audiobooks, you won't be disappointed.
This thriller had me guessing at every turn.  Just when I began to form an opinion or believe I had it figured out, Ms. Flynn threw in a new twist.  I loved it!  The suspense and intrigue kept me guessing at every turn.  I could not put this book down and found myself totally engrossed.  From sad, mad, compassionate to furious to an ending that takes you by surprise, it is unlike any mystery I have ever read.  If you love mysteries without the predictable storyline and ending, this one's for you!
Once I started this book, it ""grabbed"" me.  I read it during every spare moment over two days.  Can't wait to discuss it with the rest of my book club.  The two main characters, while fascinating, were also disgusting in their self-immersion, disregard of the law and of the feelings of others.  They deserve each other, but since they also impact the lives of others, I wish they could be punished in some way (other than by each other) for their behavior.  Interesting and enjoyable manner of story telling, different from most I've read.  Well worth the purchase price.
One of the most ingeniously plotted thrillers I have read in a long time. No male author could have pulled this off, shifting back and forth to show the different male and female viewpoints. When Part 2 kicks off - no spoilers here - it is a surprising plot twist which does shake your confidence in these characters, but as a wry and dark comment on marriages, especially the dysfunctional variety, this is one of the darkest portrayals I've ever read. Flynn's talent for crafting some poignant images, like love as the ""sweetest cancer"" will stay with readers I'm sure.
This is the best book I've read in some time.  I did not know what to expect, but the construction of the narrative hooked me immediately.  The book is initially written in first person narrative by Nick (the husband).  The story is then narrated in tag-team by an unknown diary of Nick's wife, Amy.There is a substantial amount of suspense, as the reader is looking for clues as Amy goes missing.  Does Nick know something?  Does Amy have any insight in her diaries?  Is someone keeping secrets?  The book kept me following along, like a horse being led by a carrot.
This is one of the creepiest books I have ever read in my life.  The third part of the book (it's divided into 3 sections) I finished in a marathon session because I had to know how this story would end. HIGHLY recommended.  I found this book on a Best of 2012 list and would say that it's up there in my top-ten of all time. It's such a dark, creepy story...once I got about halfway through the book (SPOILER) I really felt for the character Nick, and was very afraid of the character Amy.  And towards the end I just couldn't wait to see how it would all finally come together.
Flynn is an excellent writer, but the real joy in this book is the plotting - she has developed a really unique and effective device for telling her story, the opposing first-person accounts of a husband and wife gone bad - it is truly a page turner, and Flynn has just the right touch throughout to keep the reader engaged and thirsting for more, especially when she introduces one of several curve balls that have you saying out loud, ""Wow, I did not expect that!""This is a great read, wondefully written and plotted, one of my favorite books of all time...
WOW!!!! It's been a long time since I've read a book so intense with so much intrigue, thrill, fear --- The Shining is the last book I think of that made me have to put it down and relax before picking it up again.  Gillian Flynn is AMAZING at her craft.  It is pure genius in her character development and the plot has so many twists and turns - yet you never lose track of the storyline.  Nick & Amy and their story is....a sordid fairy tale.  So many emotions - even at the end...simply jaw-dropping.I am looking forward to reading Sharp Objects and Dark Places!!
Gone Girl has become my favorite book. I have recommended it to several others and have many of my friends reading it right now. I wanted to write a review because there are so many conflicting opinions on the book based on its ending. I thought the book was amazing from start to finish, and I am one of the rare ones that was completely happy with the way it ended. After figuring out what was going on, I had hoped for the exact ending that the book had... And I thought it was completely appropriate! I am excited for the movie but nervous to hear it has a different ending!
The only complaint about this book is that it ended too soon, I already miss the characters and wish so much that I still had Gone Girl waiting for me to pick up and read any chance I get. I KNOW those characters because Gillian Flynn is so remarkable at conception and description of them. It is a fantastic read and a fast passed journey she takes you on. I highly recommend this easy read for those who love a twisty, dark, mystery story that hooks you from beginning to end--sadly, an end that comes to soon, as I mentioned. You would think 400+ pages would be enough. Grrr.
I hate to give away anything about a book that is considered for reading. Hence, my simple one word intro,"" wild"". It is wild and unexpected, true, but way more. It is wildly readable, compelling, telling, and it leaves one panting for more. It reveals the characters completely and challenges our own norms. We see ourselves but are slightly removed: we can't really be like that... can we? I won't even say if I liked or disliked the characters, only that you must read the book and get to know them, their depth, cunning, and difference from what you expect. Read it.
This is a very interesting, intense book with many surprises along the way. The authoress has done an excellent job in identifying the flaws of being human, and the true depravity a sick mind can reach. She takes your emotions for a roller coaster ride from humor to dread to repulsion toward the characters that is rarely achieved. I have never read a book before where only a supportive character turns out to be the only character that is likable and deserving compassion.  I would hate to have any of these characters as a family member. Well done, Gillian Flynn, well done.
I had heard and read so many good reviews about this novel that my anticipation level was very high but when I started it I was wondering if I was reading the same book that everybody was talking about. Rest assured when I hit about page 150 everything fell into place and I saw what all the fuss was about. From that point it was a read until you finish book - I stayed up and lost sleep so I could see what happened next. It was so good but I do not want to spoil it for anyone else so I will just say put in the time it will be rewarded and it is not a tidy Hollywood ending.
A little confusing at first, but then I couldn't put it down. Surprise ending.
If you love a good mystery that will keep you guessing, this is the book for you.  I found myself totally invested in the characters, the outcome, the twists and turns, and did not figure out any of the plot lines before hand.  This is definitely NOT a lovely stroll through a content well-balanced marriage story.  Instead, it is a dark, disturbing tale of the horrors a couple can inflict upon one another in the supposed name of ""love"".  I was engrossed from the start and could not turn the pages fast enough!  I will go on to read Ms. Flynn's other novels as well.
The beginning of the book starts out a little slow but then hold on. There are so many twists and turns that you won't be able to put this book down. The story was reminiscent of a couple of sensational police cases that made the news. I'm an avid reader, especially of suspense novels, and I don't think I've read a book that had me guessing so much as to what would happen next. I highly recommend this book and it's author Gillian Flynn...this is only her third book and I could see it being made into a movie. I'm now reading her ""Dark Places""  and so far so good.
This is one of the best books I have ever read! I was captivated immediately.The characters are very compelling... It was difficult to decide whether I sympathized with a character or despised them... And I am not talking about just one character!  All of the characters were multi-dimensional. Amy's insights into women were especially compelling.  I found myself thinking, ""Am I like that? Do I do that? Do I behave that way?""  Gillian Flynn is a brilliant writer... She keeps you guessing throughout the book...  My mind was literally spinning! I love this book!!!
