A man, Nick, finds one day that his wife Amy has disappeared and he is soon suspected of murdering her.  This book is a subtle thriller that explores what can go wrong when two people who have been conditioned to pretend their whole lives try to make a life together.  When someone wears a mask for too long, there's a risk they'll become the mask.  While there might be an occasional flaw in this diamond, such as Nick's first person narrator sometimes holding back from the reader things he would be thinking, these don't diminish the power of this work.
Gone Girl is a very fun, enthralling read. The story is told from two points of view, husband Nick and wife Amy.  Amy is the titular missing woman.As the tale unfolds the reader keeps reassessing the situation, and the characters and their motivations.  Did Nick kill Amy? Did Desi? Was it her parents? Is she truly dead? Flynn keeps you guessing until the very end, you'll never guess the true ending.It's great. Buy it, enjoy it, tell your friends. There's a movie version coming out in October so your non-reading friends can check that out.
I found the start of the this book boring, but if you, like me, find it boring at the beginning, don't let that put the book down. The most intriguing and original book I have read in a very long time! What an imagination both on the part of the writer, Gillian Flynn, and her characters, Amy in particular. You first hate Nick, and think he weird, a cold bastard. Then all that change.  Then, you first like Amy, feel sorry for her and sympathize with her, even if she comes across as shallow, but then all that change... This book is amazingly brilliant!
Although this is not my all time favorite novel (that honor goes to 100 Years of Solitude by Gabriel Garcia Marquez), it is, by my standards, the most brilliantly crafted. I truly could not put it down. I went through all 700 plus pages in one sitting. Yet, it's not one of those archetypal, addictive thrillers, that like a snicker bar, keeps you wanting more, only to incite disappointment when it's all finished. It's one of those few novels where the style, plot line, and characters fascinate and engage, without missing a beat, from beginning to end.
Loved the perspective shifts and the humor and the twists!  Yet unlike so many novels with this much going on in terms of plot, the characters and their often darkly hilarious observations were not only entertaining, but seemed weirldy (if pathologically) realistic at least until towards the end.  Perhaps a little bit of dramatic license was necessary to keep things charging along; all I can say is that it worked and I couldn't put the book down.Can't help but think this would make an amazing movie.  Scurrying off to read more by Flynn...
