One of my favorite books last year.  Loved the back and forth in time from first person antagonist viewpoints --I can find this type of writing difficult to follow, in this case it was so well done that it enhanced the story. I was left for days later thinking about the characters, how we go through life, comparing self and how I would react to different situations.  Characters pulled me in and I still love them.  One of my 5 star requirements is a book that I'm thinking about the characters for a few days.  5 star.
This book is a mystery. As you begin, you are sure that the crime is what is, and the suspect is guilty...but is the suspect really guilty? Is it TOO obvious? The story develops in a specific way, but it changes, and you are still left wondering at the end of the story...what is happening? what are these people doing? To me, that makes a good ending. It was a different, yet interesting story. I recommend it if not for the story, then for just how the twists and turns surprise you. Makes for a very interesting read.
Gillian Flynn is brilliant at exploiting the common place, the mundane. She takes something like marriage, which has the potential to be a lifetime of happiness or go exceptionally wrong; and magnifies the nuances. Gone Girl made me question my own marriage for a hot minute. I accidentally put it under Gillian's microscope... Gone Girl made me uncomfortable, and I liked it. I have a hard time finding books that I truly get invested in. Didn't have that problem here. I read it on vacation and I couldn't put it down.
