More than a mystery, Gone Girl has woven into its narrative astute observations of what some might regard as the sociopathology of modern life in the USA. Seldom does a novel leave its reader with so much to ponder after reading instead of setting the book and its narrative aside. Simply put, Gone Girl is not gone after reading, leaving chards in the mind, fragments of discomfiture that do not dissolve easily. Patricia Highsmith has died, long live her successor.
This book was twisted and weird, and I had a really hard time putting it down. Whenever I thought I knew what was going to happen next, the story took a dramatic turn. I found myself pulling my kindle out of my purse at work because I just had to know what happened next. I even skipped yoga classes because I was too busy laying on the couch reading. I have to say I didn't really like the ending, but I highly recommend this book to anyone looking for a good story.
Gillian Flynn knows how to tell a story. Her characterizations are outstanding, which is why I ordered another of her books. She begins with two points of view, both of which show us likable people. The story unfolds, and the reader begins to like one a bit more than the other. Then the pendulum swings, and we don't know who to believe. At the end, Gone Girl left me totally satisfied with the story, the writing (which I did not constantly edit), and the outcome.
