This novel is a send-up of marriages that deteriorate when the partners cannot sustain initial facades, revealing unlikeable traits. Gone Girl depicts a woman's vindictive response to her husband’s inadequacies. The story is suspenseful and engaging with superb character development. Some reviewers have complained about the ending, but I think that the ending is entirely consistent with the theme. The novel is reminiscent of Sandrine’s Case, by Thomas H. Cook.
