Normally read the book, but saw the movie first this time. The two compliment each other nicely.  The book draws on more intricate themes than the movie, which has more shock-value. I have read all of Flynn's novels and am always impressed with her story-telling - she is unique in a way that I consider macabre, and her plots can be fascinating.
A mind boggling, endearing, addictive book. It drives you crazy and yet it makes you question everything about life. In my opinion there are only few books in the world that can leave such a lasting impact on you that you become obsessed with it. Gone Girl is a book definitely worth reading.Ps-complete the book before you watch the movie.
This psychological thriller takes the reader through heart wrenching twists and turns of plot.  This story is told through the eyes and mind of both the husband accused of murder and the wife who has disappeared.  The author uses diaries and the stories of the other characters affected by the wife's disappearance.  This was a great page turner.
While reading the book I was able to imagine the characters, scenery and moods of each situation. It was written with great detail. Not a fan of the ending, but I could live with it.I could not put the book down, as when another clue or hint was given about the character was given, it  drew me closer to finding out ""who did it!!"".
