A mind-bending psychoanalysis of marriage, replete with in-laws stories, vengeance, and parental pathos. A murder investigation reveals more than just clues about the missing Amy, it returns entertaining evidence to the reader about human nature and the status of our relationships. Gillian Flynn combines fine writing with stellar storytelling.
Love that the 3 parts make you aware that a plot change is coming, but you have no idea what it will be.  Gillian Flynn has a real gift of story-telling and can portray very specific thoughts and feelings in few words.  I read for pleasure and usually am not one to analyze literature, however I often found myself pausing in awe of her writing.
It's not often I find a book that I don't want to put down.  Gone Girl was one of those books.  I found myself thinking about the characters while I was going about my day to day business.  By the end of the book I was questioning how well I really knew the people around me.
