As the daughter of a fiction writer, I have spent most of my life discussing what makes a stellar character in any novel.Gillian Flynn hits every single aspect in Gone Girl. Her characters are witty and smart, complicated, empathetic and at times, evil and conniving. You don't know whether to love them, hate them, sympathise with them or even if you understand them at all.As a result, the book becomes so human and so real that you find yourself completely immersed in their world.In terms of plot, Flynn manages to keep you (as they say) guessing at every turn. You read the novel, thinking you understand what's really going on - that you get the characters and their separate backstories - and then Flynn will add a completely unexpected element to the story.I don't want to give any of the plot away but I'll leave with this parting statement (that I heard from another Gone Girl lover): ""If you ever want to get any work done, don't pick up Gone Girl because you will not be able to put it down.
