Gillian Flynn has a magician's talent.  In Gone Girl she accomplishes quite a trick: she writes a story in a way that totally suckers you into believing one thing...when in fact the truth turns out to be many other things.  By now the movie and book industry has desensitized us to plot elements of ""twists and turns"" and ""who done it?"" to the point that we are primed to expect it.  In this book the author manages to erase our immunity for surprise and delights us with a story that makes you feel all shinny and innocently new to these tricks of the trade.Gone Girl tells a story that readers can relate to and get invested into (as you read, before long, you'll be thinking ""oh poor darling"") and, like a car crash, keeps you from ""looking away"".  After a while it sucker punches you in a way that makes you glad you were so naive and unsuspecting.  The middle of the book just squeezes your intellectual guts as you feel bad for the character; but for whom do you feel bad?  You're just not quite sure and that is the best part.I'd tag this book as:+Yes, just do, it pick it up already+You'll be mad and glad about it+But wait there's more (the author has another 2 deliciously disturbing books to quench your thirst for this style of writing)
